<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Union, Teachers, Say Strike May End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- After negotiating through the weekend,  
representatives of both Detroit's public schools and striking 
teachers voiced optimism that a settlement was near. 
</P>
<P>
	Talks resumed Sunday morning and continued without a break until  
11 p.m. EDT, when representatives for both sides emerged with 
settlement proposals, a sign that talks had progressed to final 
stages, a district spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The dialogue was to resume at noon today.  
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully, they'll be able to work out what remains of the  
details,'' said Stan Childress, a spokesman for the district's 
interim chief executive, David Adamany. ``Both sides sounded 
optimistic that could happen'' as early as today, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	John Elliott, the president of the Detroit Federation of  
Teachers, told the Detroit Free Press in today's editions that an 
agreement on substantial issues had been reached, but that 
stumbling blocks of an economic nature remained. 
</P>
<P>
	Childress said ``all of the issues had economic implications,''  
though he declined to elaborate whether such issues included merit 
pay, which had been mentioned as a sticking point. 
</P>
<P>
	As negotiators met Sunday behind closed doors inside the Schools  
Center Building, about 125 people rallied outside to show support 
for the walkout. 
</P>
<P>
	``No more second-class education for Detroit youths,'' said Cass  
Tech High School math teacher Steve Conn. ``Equal opportunity now. 
That should be the banner at the union hall. That should be the 
banner right here at the Schools Center Building. Give Detroit 
youth and give Detroit teachers what they deserve.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The rally was organized by a group of teachers and community  
supporters who want the teachers' union to push harder for smaller 
class sizes and other concessions. The district educates 172,000 
students. 
</P>
<P>
	Conn said he believes teachers could be called as soon as  
Tuesday to vote on a new proposal. Although he has not seen what 
has been negotiated, he called on teachers to reject whatever 
contract was presented. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will likely have some reforms that we want, but I'm here to  
say it's not going to be enough. It's not what we deserve. And it's 
not really what we can get if we continue to fight,'' Conn said. 
</P>
<P>
	That was the message of speaker after speaker during the  
two-hour rally. Speakers also criticized Adamany, Mayor Dennis 
Archer, who installed a reform school board earlier this year, and 
Gov. John Engler, who supported installing the reform school board. 
</P>
<P>
	The previous contract between the school system and the 9,200  
teachers represented by the union expired June 30, and an extension 
ran out Aug. 30. Teachers voted that day to go on strike, stalling 
the scheduled start of classes. 
</P>
<P>
	A state law bans walkouts by educators. Adamany has said  
lawmakers likely would invoke that 1994 no-strike law, which fines 
teachers one day's pay for each day on strike. 
</P>
<P>
	Teachers attending the rally Sunday said they weren't worried.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to let threats scare me,'' said Reanatta  
Waldman, a special education teacher at Joy Middle School. 
</P>
<P>
	Adamany has said that if the strike continues, the school  
district plans to begin notifying other school employees Tuesday 
when they can expect layoffs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
