<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 20:20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Angels 5, Yankees 3  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Jarrod Washburn scattered five hits over  
7 2-3 innings and Troy Glaus hit a three-run homer Monday as the 
Anaheim Angels beat Roger Clemens and the New York Yankees 5-3. 
</P>
<P>
	In what looked like a pitching mismatch going into the game,  
Washburn, winless in four starts this year with a 9.15 ERA, struck 
out three and walked one to earn his first victory of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	In the longest outing of his two-year career, Washburn (1-3)  
gave up a pair of runs on solo homers by Shane Spencer, his 
seventh, in the fifth inning and Chili Davis, his 17th, in the 
sixth. 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Magnante relieved after Washburn allowed an RBI single to  
Derek Jeter with two out in the eighth. Jeter went 1-for-4 and is 
hitting .353, second in the AL to Boston's Nomar Garciaparra. 
</P>
<P>
	Troy Percival pitched the ninth for his 27th save. He struck out  
pinch-hitter Darryl Strawberry with a runner on to end the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens (12-8) got off to a rocky start, giving up Glaus' homer  
in the opening inning, then allowing a two-run shot by Jim Edmonds 
in the fifth. 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens gave up five runs and hits in 4 2-3 innings, with four  
walks and three strikeouts. Obviously having difficulty spotting 
his pitches, the hard-throwing right-hander made 103 pitches. 
</P>
<P>
	The win, only the Angels' second in their last 13 games, gave  
them the season series against New York, 6-4. They were 6-5 against 
the Yankees last year, the only team to win a season series against 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	Glaus lined a 2-2 pitch deep into the bullpen behind the left  
field fence to jump-start the Angels. The homer, his 25th, came in 
just his fourth at-bat ever against the four-time Cy Young 
Award-winner. 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens walked Edmonds and Tim Salmon with one out and got Mo  
Vaughn on a pop foul before Glaus' home run. 
</P>
<P>
	Edmonds, who has missed most of the season after undergoing  
shoulder surgery in April, gave Anaheim a four-run lead in the 
fifth when he hit Clemens' 2-0 fastball over the wall in left after 
Darin Erstad led off with a single. 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* Allen Watson replaced Clemens with two out in the fifth and  
struck out Glaus to end the inning. The left-hander, who led the 
majors in home runs allowed as a starter with the Angels, has now 
retired 13 first-batters in a row. ... Chuck Finley is expected to 
make his next scheduled start for the Angels on Friday at 
Minnesota. Finley was scratched from his turn Sunday with a lower 
back strain, but an MRI was normal. A lower back strain also kept 
Salmon out of Sunday's game, but he was the designated hitter for 
the final game of the series against New York. ... Yankees CF 
Bernie Williams missed the game with inflammation of his left 
shoulder. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
