<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                        *Byron Benton Burnes    	
</P>
<P>
	MARTINEZ, Calif. (AP) -- Byron Benton Burnes, former president of  
the National Association of the Deaf, died Aug. 25 after a brief 
illness. He was 95. 
</P>
<P>
	Burnes, known as ``B.B.B.,'' served as president of the NAD from  
1946 to 1964 and taught at the California School for the Deaf in 
Berkeley for 28 years. Burnes also taught at the Minnesota, 
Colorado and South Dakota schools for the deaf. 
</P>
<P>
	Burnes became deaf from complications from influenza and chicken  
pox when he was 15. 

</P>
<P>
                        *Marguerite Chapman    	
</P>
<P>
	BURBANK , Calif. (AP) -- Marguerite Chapman, who starred in a  
series of World War II movies and later as a secretary in Marilyn 
Monroe's film the ``The Seven Year Itch,'' died Tuesday. She was 
81. 
</P>
<P>
	From 1940 to 1943, Ms. Chapman appeared in 18 movies, ranging  
from Charlie Chan comedies to armed services booster films as a 
member of Warner Bros.' singing and dancing Navy Blues Sextet. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Chapman was eventually cast as a leading lady in  
``Destroyer'' with Edward G. Robinson and Glenn Ford and in 
``Appointment in Berlin'' opposite George Sanders. 
</P>
<P>
	After the war, she continued to win leading roles in such films  
as ``Relentless'' opposite Robert Young and ``The Green Promise'' 
with Walter Brennan. But by the 1950s, Ms. Chapman had slipped into 
supporting roles, notably as a secretary in ``The Seven Year Itch'' 
in 1955. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Chapman had top billing again in her final film, ``The  
Amazing Transparent Man'' in 1960, but the film was critically 
panned. 
</P>
<P>
	As Ms. Chapman's film career waned, she made guest appearances  
in television series including ``Richard Diamond, Private 
Detective,'' ``Rawhide,'' ``Perry Mason,'' ``Hawaii Five-0'' and 
``Marcus Welby, M.D.'' 

</P>
<P>
                         *Zaccheus Chesoni    	
</P>
<P>
	NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) -- Zaccheus Chesoni, Kenya's chief justice,  
died Sunday of a heart attack. He was 63. 
</P>
<P>
	Chesoni was chairman of Kenya's Electoral Commission when he was  
appointed chief justice by President Daniel arap Moi in December 
1997. 
</P>
<P>
	He was the second indigenous Kenyan to hold the highest judicial  
post in this East African nation since it gained independence from 
Britain in 1963. 
</P>
<P>
	Before becoming head of the Electoral Commission in 1991,  
Chesoni had been a retired judge. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Peter Gilman    	
</P>
<P>
	HILO, Hawaii (AP) -- Peter Gilman, whose best-selling novel was  
turned into the movie ``Diamond Head,'' died Wednesday. He was 73. 
</P>
<P>
	Gilman was a reporter for The Honolulu Star-Bulletin in the  
1950s when he wrote ``Such Sweet Thunder,'' which topped The New 
York Times Best Seller List. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia Pictures paid $100,000 for the book in 1959. The novel  
was turned into the 1960 movie ``Diamond Head,'' starring Charlton 
Heston. 
</P>
<P>
	Following his success, Gilman moved to Paris, where he joined a  
group of fellow-expatriate writers that included James Jones, James 
Baldwin and William Styron. 
</P>
<P>
	Gilman later trained polo ponies in Argentina, and became an  
artist and commercial fisherman in Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	Born in New York, Gilman graduated from UCLA, and went on to  
work for the Monterey Peninsula Herald in California, The 
Associated Press and The Los Angeles Times. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include three sons.  

</P>
<P>
                          *David McFarland    	
</P>
<P>
	PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) -- David McFarland, an editor, columnist and  
writing coach at the Pensacola News Journal, died of a heart attack 
Sunday. He was 40. 
</P>
<P>
	McFarland died just hours after helping get to press the  
newspaper's Sunday editions. 
</P>
<P>
	``His death has broken the heart of this newsroom,'' said  
Executive Editor Randy Hammer. 
</P>
<P>
	Colleagues praised McFarland's ability to direct and shape young  
reporters, his keen news judgment and his talent for editing. 
</P>
<P>
	His conversational Sunday column often revolved around local  
news events. The column also carried his gentle, self-deprecating 
humor evidenced in stories of his close knit family. 
</P>
<P>
	McFarland, who grew up in Birmingham, Ala., also worked at the  
Alabama Journal in Montgomery, Ala.; the Sarasota Herald-Tribune, 
the Palm Beach Review and The Anniston (Ala.) Star. 
</P>
<P>
	He is survived by his father, two half-brothers and a  
half-sister. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Stanley Weigel    	
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Stanley Weigel , a retired federal judge  
who made decisions on school desegregation and the U.S. involvement 
in Nicaragua, died Wednesday a few months after suffering a stroke. 
He was 93. 
</P>
<P>
	Weigel ordered the city's schools desegregated in 1971. In the  
1980s, he backed attempts to uncover U.S. involvement in Nicaragua 
and issued rulings that led to improved living conditions for state 
prison inmates. 
</P>
<P>
	After serving as a Navy officer during World War II, Weigel  
returned to private practice and defended 31 members of the 
University of California faculty who were fired for refusing to 
sign oaths that they did not belong to the Communist Party. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1952, the state Supreme Court ordered the professors  
reinstated. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990906.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 20:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Probe Ordered Into N.M. Prison </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- The state's top prison and law  
enforcement officials announced an investigation Monday into why a 
privately run prison didn't notify state police about a riot in 
which a guard was stabbed to death. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-hour riot Aug. 31 at the medium-security Guadalupe  
County Correctional Facility in Santa Rosa left one guard dead and 
an inmate wounded. The prison is run by Florida-based Wackenhut 
Corrections Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said Wackenhut didn't notify state police about the  
riot and told the state Corrections Department at least an hour 
after the two men were stabbed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I won't hesitate for a New York minute to push for charges  
against somebody if their actions jeopardize the lives of the 
corrections officers in that facility or my own officers who 
responded to that riot,'' Public Safety Secretary Darren White 
said. ``If warranted I would go to the top of the corporate 
ladder.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wackenhut spokesman Pat Cannan has said he would not comment on  
White's criticisms. A woman at Wackenhut headquarters said that 
Cannan was unavailable for comment until Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Corrections Secretary Rob Perry said he plans to gather  
independent prison experts from around the country to review the 
situation. State investigators will assist the panel. 
</P>
<P>
	Wackenhut runs more than two dozen prisons nationwide.  
</P>
<P>
	In the past nine months, four inmates and a guard have died in  
Wackenhut-run prisons in New Mexico. In addition, two guards were 
injured in a disturbance Aug. 17 at a prison run by another 
company. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990906.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 20:20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wal-Mart Heirs Buy St. Louis Blues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Fresh from a failure to buy a sports empire in  
Denver, Wal-Mart heirs Bill and Nancy Laurie have purchased the St. 
Louis Blues and Kiel Center. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale, which coincided with the opening of the Blues'  
training camp, was announced late Monday afternoon in a statement 
released by the team. Terms of the sale were not immediately 
disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	The purchase caps a months-long effort by the Lauries, a  
Columbia, Mo., couple, to enter the world of professional sports 
ownership, and a nearly year-long effort by the partnership that 
owned the Blues to recoup its investment. In March, the Lauries 
were unsuccessful in their attempt to buy the NHL's Colorado 
Avalanche and the NBA's Denver Nuggets and their new home, the 
Pepsi Center. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nancy and I are looking forward to building on the strong  
Blues hockey tradition in the St. Louis community,'' Bill Laurie 
said in a statement. ``We have been searching for the right sports 
opportunity for several years and, to our delight, we found it 
right down the road.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Laurie planned to meet with the team Tuesday morning, with  
an 11 a.m. (CST) news conference at the Kiel Center to follow. The 
Lauries are the second Columbia entry into the St. Louis sports 
market in recent years; Stan Kroenke is a minority owner of the 
NFL's St. Louis Rams. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lauries were at a movie in Columbia on Monday night, and did  
not immediately return a call to The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lauries' Denver deal fell through when shareholders of  
Ascent Entertainment Group, which owned the sports properties, 
filed suit, claiming the $400 million sale price was as much as 
$150 million too low. An out-of-court settlement resulted in an 
auction. 
</P>
<P>
	Several groups of investors, including one led by former Denver  
Broncos quarterback John Elway, bid on the teams and the arena. The 
winner of that auction, a group headed by Colorado billionaire 
Donald Strum, was then to bid one-on-one against the Lauries. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lauries declined to take part in the $1 million-per-bid  
second auction, and Strum bought Ascent's sport assests for $461 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Kiel Partners, a consortium of local businessmen that owns the  
Blues, announced Dec. 30 that it had hired Goldman Sachs, a New 
York investment bank, to explore the team's financial options. They 
included selling the Blues, selling Kiel Center, bringing an NBA 
team to the city, or overhauling Kiel Center's capital structure, 
which includes $96 million in debt. 
</P>
<P>
	Two months ago, Kiel Parters officially announced that the team  
was for sale. 
</P>
<P>
	The partnership said it pumped more than $70 million into the  
team and Kiel Center over the previous four years to cover 
shortfalls. 
</P>
<P>
	This is the third NHL team to change hands this year. Deals for  
two or three more are pending or in the works. 
</P>
<P>
	Nancy Walton Laurie is the daughter of the late Bud Walton, who  
with his late brother Sam co-founded Wal-Mart. Bill Laurie is a 
former basketball player at Memphis State, and he and his wife own 
Crown Center Farms in Columbia, where they raise quarter horses and 
Appaloosas. 
</P>
<P>
	The couple made the largest single donation to the University of  
Missouri in its history in 1996, offering $10 million toward the 
constuction of a new basketball arena. The donation was withdrawn a 
year later after the Lauries felt the university wasn't make enough 
progress toward its construction. 
</P>
<P>
	Stan Kronke, who is married to Nancy's sister and fellow  
Wal-Mart heir Ann, is a minority owner of the St. Louis Rams. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blues made it to the second round of the playoffs last  
season, losing to the eventual Stanley Cup champion Dallas Stars in 
six games. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
