<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 23:20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> States May Get Little From Financier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	So far, regulators have seized $57.5 million of Martin Frankel's  
assets and are eyeing millions more in a frozen Swiss bank account. 
</P>
<P>
	Frankel is believed to have embezzled at least $218 million, and  
now regulators are hoping he will help them recover it, presumably 
in a bid for leniency. 
</P>
<P>
	Frankel was arrested in Germany on Saturday night, ending a  
four-month international manhunt for the 44-year-old alleged rogue 
financier. But if state officials were expecting cooperation, his 
German lawyer, Thomas Piplak, said Frankel is considering fighting 
extradition to avoid possible retribution from those he is accused 
of cheating. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators have linked at least three foreign bank accounts --  
in Switzerland, Italy and Germany -- to Frankel, said Keith Wenzel, 
director of Missouri's Department of Insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	State regulators also hope they'll be able to liquidate homes,  
diamonds and jewels belonging to Frankel, Wenzel said Monday. 
Frankel may have been financing his run with more than $10 million 
in diamonds and gold he bought before fleeing, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some regulators doubt they'll recover much more than they've  
already identified. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't feel like they're counting on full recovery,'' said  
Marilyn Elam, a spokeswoman for Tennessee's Department of Commerce 
and Insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal investigators say Frankel used pseudonyms and partners  
to buy small insurance companies in states with reputations for lax 
insurance regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, regulators said, Frankel's unlicensed brokerage --  
apparently run out of his $3 million Greenwich, Conn., mansion -- 
siphoned money from the companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Now regulators in those states -- Mississippi, Arkansas,  
Tennessee, Oklahoma and Missouri -- are banding together to recover 
the lost funds. Tennessee managed to seize $57.5 million, and has 
given $17.5 million of that to other states. 
</P>
<P>
	It is the states, not insurance policyholders, that would lose  
if the insurers remain in the red. 
</P>
<P>
	The states guaranteed the policies and will have to pay any  
amount not recovered from the insolvent insurance companies. Most 
of the policies, including 12,000 in Tennessee, are burial plans 
worth several thousand dollars apiece. 
</P>
<P>
	It could be a long wait before any money changes hands.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're hoping to have it wrapped up within a couple of years,''  
Wenzel said. 
</P>
<P>
	Frankel might still spend months in custody in Germany, where he  
was captured by federal and international authorities, even if he 
waived extradition to the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Insurance companies can spend a year or longer in receivership  
in a typical case, and ``this one is more complicated than most,'' 
said John Knox Walkup, the former Tennessee attorney general who is 
handling the receivership of the Tennessee insurer, Franklin 
American. 
</P>
<P>
	Auditors are still trying to understand how much money is  
missing. A lawsuit filed by some of the companies puts the loss at 
$915 million, but Wenzel said: ``I don't think any of the 
regulators ever thought it was that high.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Frankel also is thought to have allegedly stolen as much as  
$1.98 billion from the St. Francis of Assisi Foundation, which 
investigators say he established last year in the British Virgin 
Islands. 
</P>
<P>
	But it's unclear whether much -- if any -- of that money ever  
existed or whether Frankel merely claimed it was there. The 
foundation was set up as a charity that bought insurance companies, 
investigators said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
