<DOCNO> APW19990906.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 13:50:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Notre Dame's Party Started Too Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) -- The least excessive celebration in the  
entire state might have been the one Notre Dame receiver Bobby 
Brown staged after catching a 2-point conversion pass in the 
Michigan end zone. Thanks to some hair-trigger officiating, it also 
turned out to be one of the most costly. 
</P>
<P>
	``Should he have done it?'' Irish coach Bob Davie asked Sunday  
without waiting for an answer. ``No. Does he know he made a 
mistake? Yes. Will he do it again? No. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's just unfortunate,'' he added, ``that it had an impact on  
the game like it did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though Davie went on to defend the excessive celebration rule  
and the NCAA's no-nonsense interpretation -- ``I'm an advocate of 
making it tight,'' the coach said -- it's also clear he was still 
smarting from the sting of Michigan's breath-stealing 26-22 win 
over Notre Dame on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The result wasn't secured until the clock ran out on a final  
Irish drive at the Wolverines 12, but the moment that caused 
college football's latest controversy came at the 4:08 mark. That's 
when Brown caught a pass from quarterback Jarious Jackson in the 
corner of the end zone, jumped to his feet, stuck both his thumbs 
into the ear holes of his helmet, and facing the crowd, imitated a 
moose with wriggling antlers. 
</P>
<P>
	The officials immediately whistled Brown for celebrating  
``excessively'' and slapped a 15-yard penalty on the Irish, sending 
them back to their own 20 for the ensuing kickoff. Michigan running 
back Anthony Thomas, inserted into the middle of the return 
formation for just such an occasion, then fielded the kick and 
returned it 20 yards to the Notre Dame 42. 
</P>
<P>
	As if making a last stand with almost half the field already in  
front of them wasn't tough enough on the Irish defense, Notre Dame 
safety Ron Israel got whistled for a hit out of bounds two plays 
later. That gave Michigan another large chunk of real estate, and 
with 1:38 left to play, Thomas crashed into the end zone from 2 
yards out with what proved to be the decisive score. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown defended himself at first, saying, ``It was just something  
personal. I thought because I did it quick, he (the official) 
wouldn't see it. It was pure excitement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As it turns out, the gesture might have been less innocent than  
that. At Michigan Stadium, members of the band roam through the 
crowd during the game, serenading sections with the theme from the 
cartoon show, ``Rocky and Bullwinkle.'' The fans respond by doing 
what most of us would call a moose, but what veterans of the 
stadium call a ``Bullwinkle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As a senior who's played at Ann Arbor before, Brown likely would  
have been familiar with the gesture -- and the veteran officiating 
crew working the game even more so. 
</P>
<P>
	``I could be a coward or a man about it,'' Brown said. ``I'm  
mature enough not to run away from saying I might have cost my team 
a game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, you can't pass a playground today without seeing the same  
gesture being traded back and forth a dozen times. And this one, 
lasting barely seconds, took place in the overheated cauldron of 
the Big House, as Michigan Stadium is known, on a 90-degree day 
near the end of one of the most exciting contests in one of the 
most storied and passionate rivalries the game has to offer. At the 
moment Brown caught the ball, there were 111,523 fans looking on -- 
the largest crowd to see a college football game -- most of them 
wildly partisan Wolverine fans. 
</P>
<P>
	And because he got up and imitated a moose for an instant, he's  
the one guilty of taunting? 
</P>
<P>
	Apparently so.  
</P>
<P>
	The excessive celebration rule has been around for a half-dozen  
seasons, but it was tightened considerably in 1995. Then, a 12-man 
NCAA committee culled examples of what it considered over-the-top 
celebrating and packaged a 30-minute film for schools, conferences, 
coaches and officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Georgia athletic director Vince Dooley, who was chairman of the  
NCAA football rules committee at the time, said, ``What we're going 
to eliminate is when it goes from spontaneity to delayed, prolonged 
activity. Some of these things are even rehearsed. You can tell.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When the National Football League clamped down on celebrating,  
fans started complaining that the acronym NFL stood for the ``No 
Fun League.'' Davie disagreed with a subsequent decision by the pro 
league to relax the rule, saying what he sees on some Sundays 
leaves a bad taste in his mouth. 
</P>
<P>
	``How do you monitor what is (excessive) and what isn't?'' he  
said. ``It's hard. And I think the NCAA does a tremendous job with 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In this case, they might have done the job a little too well.  
</P>
<P>
	What Brown did Saturday wasn't excessive. But by helping  
Michigan win its season opener, he certainly contributed to some 
partying that was excessive by the time Saturday night rolled 
around. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is the national sports columnist for The Associated  
Press. Write to him at jlitke@ap.org. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
