<DOCNO> APW19990906.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 14:30:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Badgers Not Worried About Injuries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- Wisconsin will be one receiver short when  
it takes the field Saturday against Ball State. 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Chambers, the only Big Ten Conference wideout to average  
more than 20 yards per catch last season, broke a bone in his right 
hand in the ninth-ranked Badgers' 39-point season-opening win over 
Murray State. 
</P>
<P>
	``The more he catches, the more he gets those fingers hit with  
the ball. It would just keep irritating that bone so they felt if 
he stayed out and not catch the ball for a while he could heal that 
up fairly quickly,'' coach Barry Alvarez said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Nick Davis, a sophomore flanker and kick returner, will step in  
at split end for Chambers, Alvarez said. Davis played at the wide 
receiver position early on in his freshman season and led Wisconsin 
with three receptions for 57 yards against UCLA in the Rose Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel pretty comfortable at the split end position,'' Davis  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ahmad Merritt played more minutes Saturday after Chambers went  
out with the injury, catching three passes for 63 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ahmad came up huge for us,'' quarterback Scott Kavanagh said.  
``I've got a lot of good receivers. I've got all the confidence in 
the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alvarez said he would not speculate whether Chambers would be  
able to play at Cincinnati on Sept. 18. 
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, Wisconsin not only has Davis and Merritt  
available to play at receiver, but can also look to sophomore 
Conroy Whyte and freshman Lee Evans. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got better depth right now at wide receiver, ... by far  
the best depth that we've had,'' Alvarez said. ``If there's one 
position where we have any luxury to lose a top guy it would be 
there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wide receiver Demetrius Brown injured his knee on the same drive  
as Chambers but Alvarez said he was likely to play Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Demetrius is walking very well today ... but I think he's got  
a chance to play,'' Alvarez said. ``He really looked pretty good 
today.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
