<HEADLINE> Kent Desormeaux Injured in Spill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DEL MAR, Calif. (AP) -- Kent Desormeaux, one of thoroughbred  
racing's top jockeys, broke two bones in his wrist and sustained a 
deep leg bruise Monday in a spill at Del Mar. 
</P>
<P>
	Desormeaux was taken to Scripps Memorial Hospital in nearby La  
Jolla after being thrown from his mount, The Key Rainbow, the 3-2 
favorite in the 10th race. 
</P>
<P>
	There were no apparent injuries to the horse.  
</P>
<P>
	Desormeaux, who injured his right wrist and upper left leg, will  
be sidelined indefinitely, according to track spokesman Dan Smith. 
</P>
<P>
	The 29-year-old jockey was attempting to get The Key Rainbow  
between Isle Of Man and Zippersup in midstretch when Zippersup bore 
in. 
</P>
<P>
	The Key Rainbow appeared to clip heels and fell, with Desormeaux  
falling in front of the horse. 
</P>
<P>
	Desormeaux, who rode Real Quiet to victories in the 1998  
Kentucky Derby and Preakness, was treated briefly at the track 
before being transported to the hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	Zippersup, ridden by David Flores, finished third behind  
Embraceable You and Isle of Man in the one-mile race on turf, but 
was disqualified and placed last following a stewards' inquiry. 
Vaclav was moved up to third. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
