<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Natwest Bids for Legal &AMP; General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- National Westminster Bank PLC on Monday announced  
a $17.2 billion agreement to take over life insurance and pension 
provider Legal &AMP; General Group PLC. But some analysts considered 
the bid risky and expensive, and investors bid both companies' 
shares down. 
</P>
<P>
	Shareholders in Legal &AMP; General will get $3.37 a share in cash  
and stock. The price puts a slight premium on the $3.30 at which 
Legal &AMP; General traded Friday after news broke of the takeover bid. 
But it constitutes a hefty 20 percent premium on the price earlier 
last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``We deem it a fair price,'' NatWest chief executive David  
Wanless said. ``We're buying an exceptional business and are 
creating a complete financial services company.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, NatWest shares, which had fallen Friday on rumors of  
the deal, slipped further, trading at $18.20 on the London Stock 
Exchange, down from $18.34. 
</P>
<P>
	Legal &AMP; General eased to $3.24, but still was buoyed by the  
prospect of becoming part of a significant new force in the British 
financial services market. 
</P>
<P>
	``This could be a transforming deal turning it into a real  
powerhouse. But it's not without risks,'' said David Raye, an 
analyst at HSBC Securities in London. 
</P>
<P>
	``Half of us think they paid too much and half too little. It's  
a full price and there's got to be real growth there ... but it's 
not inconceivable it could be achieved,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	There also are doubts about whether selling life insurance and  
pensions through banks can be made to work in Britain. 
</P>
<P>
	If the deal -- which needs shareholder approval -- goes through,  
the merged group would have a value of about $48 billion and employ 
76,000 people. The two companies said the takeover would mean 
annual cost savings of some $208 million by the end of 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	Anticipated savings would be achieved by merging the two  
company's life and general insurance businesses, fund management 
and head office functions. 
</P>
<P>
	NatWest will finance the offer by issuing new shares, borrowing  
and tapping internal funds. NatWest shareholders would hold about 
75 percent of the combined company's shares and Legal &AMP; General 
shareholders the rest. 
</P>
<P>
	Although there had been no shortage of proposals from investment  
banks, ``there's never been a proposition that has had this kind of 
business fit,'' Legal &AMP; General Chief Executive David Prosser said. 
</P>
<P>
	NatWest chairman Sir David Rowland would be chairman of the  
merged group and Wanless, NatWest's chief executive, deputy 
chairman. Prosser would also be deputy chairman, but would report 
to Wanless. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
