<DOCNO> APW19990906.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 13:10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> California May Require Booster Seats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FREEDOM, Calif. (AP) -- Donny Baltazar rides proudly to  
kindergarten every morning in the front passenger seat, toying with 
the large, loose seat belt that slides up over his mouth. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like it up here in front,'' he says. ``I like to play with  
the seat belt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Donny's been riding shotgun for two years, ever since his mom,  
Marguerita Baltazar, took him out of the car seat mandated in 
California for children under 4 years old and 40 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	But safety advocates point out that seat belts can be as  
dangerous to children as air bags. They say California's law 
doesn't go far enough. Children as old as 6 also are usually too 
small for a seat belt designed for an adult. The shoulder straps 
slide dangerously up their necks, and the lap belts sit across 
their vulnerable abdomens, not low on their hips. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Gray Davis is considering a measure passed by the  
Legislature last week that will put kids like Donny back into 
booster seats or harnesses through their seventh birthday. The 
devices cost $20 to $110. 
</P>
<P>
	If signed, it will be the toughest child passenger safety law in  
the country. 
</P>
<P>
	``Children are irreplaceable,'' said Judy Barrett-Miller, a  
consultant for the California Coalition For Children's Safety And 
Health in Sacramento. ``Traffic accidents are the leading cause of 
death for children who this law applies to. If we want to safeguard 
our children, this is the best approach.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A National Highway Traffic Safety Administration study of  
traffic accidents involving children under 15 found that 71 percent 
of deaths and 66 percent of injuries could be eliminated if the 
children used an appropriate child safety seat, booster seat or 
seat belt on every ride. 
</P>
<P>
	California Highway Patrol officer Debby Bratby -- who sees  
first-hand the dangers children face in car accidents -- wouldn't 
dream of driving her 5-year-old daughter anywhere without buckling 
her into a booster seat. 
</P>
<P>
	``The seat belt could come across the neck, and in children that  
windpipe is real sensitive, so it could kill them. And then there's 
the internal injuries that can be caused by the lap belt,'' she 
said. ``Parents just aren't aware of the dangers. We really need 
this law.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All 50 states, the District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, and the  
U.S. territories have car seat laws, most of which cover children 
up to about 4 years old. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumer and safety advocates say those laws have saved  
thousands of lives. From 1979, when no states had car seat 
requirements, until 1984, when most had been enacted, deaths among 
children under 4 dropped 30 percent nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, supporters of the new law say, it's time to protect the 4,  
5 and 6 year olds. 
</P>
<P>
	Alabama and Massachusetts require booster seats or harnesses for  
children who have grown out of their car seats, but those laws only 
apply to children under 6, one year less than the California 
measure. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill also would boost the potential fine for a second  
violation of child-seat requirements to $250, although violators 
could take classes in lieu of the fine. 
</P>
<P>
	State Sen. Jackie Speier, who sponsored the legislation, said  
it's unsafe to simply use seat belts to restrain 4- to 6-year-olds. 
</P>
<P>
	``We dump them into a car's seat belt that's designed for a man  
weighing about 168 pounds,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Assemblyman Bruce Thompson opposed the bill, saying it  
represents government prying unnecessarily into the lives of loving 
parents. 
</P>
<P>
	``They don't want the government to come in and tell them what  
to do,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lorena Roche of Watsonville said she had no idea that her  
children -- 4-year-old Joe and 5-year-old Anna -- were unsafe in seat 
belts. 
</P>
<P>
	``I kept them in the car seats, just like the law says, until  
they were old enough,'' she said. ``I certainly would put them in 
something else if it would be safer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The new law, if signed, wouldn't take effect until Jan. 1, 2001,  
allowing time for a broad, statewide education effort. Plans 
include television and print advertising, and in-school training. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Baltazar said she realizes Donny could be safer.  
</P>
<P>
	``I know it wouldn't be as dangerous if he was in a car seat,  
but he really wouldn't like it and I would have to hear about it,'' 
she said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
