<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EU Unemployment Falls to 9.3 Pct. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) - Unemployment in the European Union fell  
to 9.3 percent in July from 9.4 percent in June, the EU's 
statistics office reported Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The jobless rate was 10.3 percent in July 1998.  
</P>
<P>
	The EU unemployment rate compared to 4.3 percent in the United  
States in July and 4.9 percent in Japan. The U.S. unemployment rate 
fell in August to 4.2 percent, matching the 29-year low reached in 
March and May. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 11 nations that use Europe's single currency, the euro,  
unemployment fell to 10.2 percent in July from 10.3 in June, 
according to Eurostat's monthly report. In July 1998, the 
unemployment rate in the euro-zone nations was 10.9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Luxembourg continued to register the lowest unemployment in the  
EU, at 2.8 percent. Spain had the highest at 15.9 percent, although 
the Spanish jobless rate also registered the fastest fall over the 
year, from 18.8. 
</P>
<P>
	Eurostat gave the following July 1999 figures for the 15 EU  
countries, with June figures in brackets: 
</P>
<P>
	Luxembourg, 2.8 percent (2.8); Austria, 4.3 (4.3); Portugal, 4.5  
(4.7); Ireland 6.7 (6.7); Sweden 6.8 (7); Belgium, 9 (9); Germany, 
9.1 (9.1); Finland, 9.8 (10.1); France, 11 (11.2), Spain 15.9 
(16.1). 
</P>
<P>
	July figures were unavailable for some nations. The Netherlands  
registered 3.2 percent in June, down from 3.3 in May; Denmark's 
unemployment held steady in June at 4.5. Latest figures from 
Britain registered unemployment in May at 6.1 percent and Italy's 
most recent data showed 12 percent in April. 
</P>
<P>
	Eurostat released no data on Greece.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
