<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 16:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Underdog Bruins Remain Confident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- UCLA coach Bob Toledo realizes his team is  
facing Ohio State at the worst possible time. 
</P>
<P>
	And he expects the Bruins to beat the Buckeyes.  
</P>
<P>
	Apparently, his players feel the same way.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're UCLA, we're going to tell our kids that,'' Toledo said  
Monday. ``We're going to respect our opponents, they better have 
some respect for us, too. We have a pretty good program. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're to go back there and play our hearts out, we're going to  
play to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the surface, it doesn't look good for UCLA.  
</P>
<P>
	--The 14th-ranked Bruins (1-0) will face the 13th-ranked Buckeyes  
(0-1) without 11 players -- most of them starters -- who were 
suspended for the season's first two games for illegally obtaining 
handicapped parking permits. 
</P>
<P>
	--The Bruins will also be without pass rushing specialist Travor  
Turner, who sustained a season-ending knee injury in UCLA's 38-7 
victory over Boise State on Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	--UCLA might also be without standout wide receiver Danny Farmer,  
who caught 58 passes for 1,274 yards and nine touchdowns last 
season. Farmer missed the opener because of a sprained ankle, and 
his status for the Ohio State game is uncertain. 
</P>
<P>
	--The Buckeyes, 23-12 losers to No. 8 Miami in the Kickoff  
Classic on Aug. 29, haven't started a season with two losses since 
1986. That means Ohio State will have had 13 days to lick its 
wounds and prepare for the Bruins, who, mainly because of the 
suspensions, will field an inexperienced team against an angry 
opponent before a hostile crowd of about 94,000. 
</P>
<P>
	--The Buckeyes have won 20 straight home openers, and have won 32  
of their last 33 non-conference games at Ohio Stadium dating to a 
23-20 loss to Stanford in 1982. 
</P>
<P>
	The only loss since then came on Sept. 22, 1990, when Southern  
California beat Ohio State 35-26. 
</P>
<P>
	``They'll be ready to play,'' Toledo said of the Buckeyes.  
``Hopefully, our players will be ready as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm looking forward to it; playing a team like this is one of  
the reasons our players came to school here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Toledo admitted he kept his team under wraps somewhat against  
Boise State. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to do a few things, try to do them well, get out with  
a win,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Junior quarterback Drew Bennett, who struggled in the first half  
against Boise State in his first career start but was much better 
in the second half, realizes his second start will be against a 
much better opponent in a different atmosphere. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, he expressed confidence.  
</P>
<P>
	``If you don't think you can win, there's no point,'' he said.  
``If we can pull this one out and get all our guys back (from 
suspension), I think we'll have something to feed off. We'll have a 
real intimidating team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bennett and freshman Cory Paus alternated against Boise State,  
and Toledo said the plan will be the same against Ohio State. But 
within the next few weeks, he'll settle on one quarterback to play 
the majority of the time. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's quite a challenge,'' Paus said of facing the Buckeyes.  
``You can't ask for anything more for a second game. The earlier, 
the better. I'm sure I'll be a little nervous, the normal person 
would be. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to have to work a little harder this week because  
we're going to be facing a better team. If you can (be successful) 
against one team, there's no reason you can't do it against 
another.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Freshman defensive back Ricky Manning, impressive against Boise  
State in his first college game with seven tackles, including three 
for losses, said he's been looking forward to facing Ohio State all 
summer. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's going to be a lot of hard hitting, a lot of trash  
talking, a lot of smash-mouth,'' he said. ``That's just how it is. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we can beat Ohio State. I've watched them on film;  
they're a good team but I'm not overwhelmed by them. The best 
team's going to win. You can't go into a game thinking you're going 
to lose.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
