<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 16:00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Comeback Excites Giants' Williams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- After missing the last two seasons  
with an eye injury, you better believe Brian Williams is excited 
heading into the New York Giants' regular-season opener at Tampa 
Bay on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	While Williams isn't acting like a giddy rookie, the veteran  
Giants center admitted this game is going to be special after what 
he has been through since a freakish poke in the eye nearly ended 
his career. 
</P>
<P>
	One obvious sign was the way the 11-year veteran reacted last  
week when he watched game film prior to the exhibition finale 
against Baltimore. Knowing he wasn't going to play because of a 
bruised knee, Williams felt his mind wandering. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't wait,'' Williams said after returning to practice  
Monday. ``After I banged my knee, I woke up and all I thought about 
was Tampa Bay. I couldn't help it. I'm really excited. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's totally different tempo out there,'' the 33-year-old  
added. ``You'll see totally different things as far as the 
defenses. There will be a lot more big plays out there in the game. 
It's exciting. I can't wait.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams hasn't played in a regular season game since the Giants  
faced New England in the final game of the 1996 season. 
</P>
<P>
	On the third day of the 1997 training camp, he was poked in the  
right eye by defensive lineman Bernard Holsey during a blocking 
drill. The blow fractured the eye orbit and caused double vision, 
which didn't clear until this past December following a couple of 
surgeries. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams has tried to downplay his return, but it's been obvious  
he is a steadying influence on a line that performed badly last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I bring different things to the game and things to the  
team, but I am not a missing link,'' Williams insisted. ``I never 
felt that way. I just feel I am another player in there, and I work 
well with the other guys and they work well with me. That's what 
matters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coming back has not been a snap for Williams. Early in camp he  
criticized his own blocking techniques, and felt he was slow 
adjusting to some of the defensive fronts. He also wondered how 
well he would play after the long layoff. 
</P>
<P>
	Now comes the real thing, and the Buccaneers are going to be a  
test with a defensive line that features a trimmed down and even 
quicker Warren Sapp. 
</P>
<P>
	``This will be a big test for me as far as where I'm at,''  
Williams said. ``As far as being in with the guys and knowing my 
plays and assignments and recognition of the defenses, I feel 
pretty confident.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of the major concerns for the Giants coming into the game  
will be the rookie guard to the left of Williams, first round draft 
pick Luke Petticoat. He was forced into the starting lineup two 
weeks ago after Lance Scott tore up his knee. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams has taken Petticoat under his wing. All this week, he  
has been talking to the former Notre Dame tackle discussing 
coverage. 
</P>
<P>
	Before each play, they double check their assignments and then  
point out the middle linebacker to each other. It's really not 
necessary, but it's a way of making the rookie feel comfortable. 
</P>
<P>
	The Giants need that because they did not get the running game  
going in the preseason, and they are coming into the season opener 
without leading rusher Gary Brown, who sprained a knee last week. 
He'll be out three to four weeks, leaving rookie Sean Bennett and 
cancer-survivor LeShon Johnson to carry the load. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams isn't worried.  
</P>
<P>
	``As far as the line goes, we are very confident in who is going  
to be back there,'' Williams said. ``On the other hand, the line 
has to improve on the running game. We have to step it up this 
week. These guys are great pass rushers, and they will put a lot of 
heat on us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But that's what he has been waiting for.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990906.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 13:22:45 </DATE_TIME>
