<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Monday, Sept. 6, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Detroit Schools Want Strike Settled  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Amid hints that a settlement could be close,  
striking teachers brought their message to the street today, toting 
signs saying ``No contract, no work'' as they marched in the city's 
Labor Day parade. Negotiations between teachers and the school 
board resumed today, with district officials voicing optimism about 
reaching a deal on Labor Day. ``Both sides have indicated that 
today we could likely see a settlement,'' a district spokesman 
said. ``I do know that all of the issues that had been on the table 
were embodied in the final settlement package.'' 

</P>
<P>
	School Security Raises Concerns  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As children head back to school,  
security-conscious school administrators are also having to think 
about students' rights. Police officers, metal detectors, student 
ID cards and surveillance cameras are part of life in the nation's 
schools as a result of tragedies such as last April's incident in 
which two Columbine High School students gunned down a dozen 
classmates and a teacher before killing themselves. Nadine 
Strossen, national president of the American Civil Liberties Union, 
says ``students' privacy rights and freedom of speech are under 
attack from within.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Pro-Indonesia Forces Terrorize Dili  
</P>
<P>
	DILI, Indonesia (AP) -- Tens of thousands of refugees fled the  
capital of East Timor today as pro-Indonesia militias continued a 
wave of terror, torching homes and reportedly slaughtering hundreds 
of civilians. World leaders indignantly called for Indonesia to 
make good on its pledge to provide security in the provincial 
capital, Dili. But witnesses said Indonesian troops were aiding the 
militias and trying to intimidate journalists and U.N. workers into 
fleeing the territory. ``The situation remains out of control,'' a 
police chief said. ``The government there is no longer 
functioning.'' 

</P>
<P>
	MIAs Top U.S. Concerns in Vietnam  
</P>
<P>
	HANOI, Vietnam (AP) -- When it comes to Vietnam, trade and  
economic issues are important, but Secretary of State Madeleine 
Albright made it clear today that accounting for American MIAs is 
still the top priority. Albright, making a two-day stopover en 
route to the Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation summit in New 
Zealand, expressed gratitude for Vietnamese cooperation in tracking 
down and recovering the remains of former U.S. soldiers. 

</P>
<P>
	Five Arrested in Israel Car Bombings  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Declaring that their common task is fighting  
terrorism, Israel and the Palestinians expressed hope today that a 
pair of car bombings will not knock the newly revived peace process 
off track. Police said five arrests were made in yesterday's 
bombings in northern Israel. Authorities kept the identities of 
those taken into custody secret-- as well as those of the three 
slain men, apparently the bombers. A court said the gag order was 
requested because the investigation could uncover plans for 
further, imminent attacks. 

</P>
<P>
	Rebels Kill 14 Russian Troops  
</P>
<P>
	MAKHACHKALA, Russia (AP) -- Fourteen Russian troops died today in  
a shootout with Islamic militants, while residents of the southern 
republic of Dagestan became increasingly angry that federal forces 
have failed to oust the rebels despite a month of fighting. The 
militants, seeking an independent Islamic state, have battled 
Russian troops since seizing several villages in Dagestan on Aug. 
7. Government troops have pushed the rebels out of some areas, but 
renewed violence has made clear that the militants are still intent 
on attacking Russian targets. 

</P>
<P>
	'Sixth Sense' Soars at Box Office  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- ``The Sixth Sense'' remained the top  
box-office draw for the fifth straight weekend with a 
record-breaking take for the four-day Labor Day weekend. ``Sixth 
Sense,'' starring Bruce Willis in the tale of a boy who's a magnet 
for the walking dead, took in $28.5 million, according to industry 
estimates today. That's nearly as much as the grosses for the rest 
of the top five films, which took in a combined $30.1 million. 

</P>
<P>
	Qualifier Defeats Rios at U.S. Open  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Nicolas Escude of France became the first  
qualifier in the Open era to reach the quarterfinals of the U.S. 
Open today when he upset 10th-seeded Marcelo Rios 6-2, 6-3, 7-5. 
Also moving into the quarterfinals was No. 2 Andre Agassi, who 
breezed past Arnaud Clement of France 6-4, 6-4, 6-3. Among the 
women, No. 4 Monica Seles and No. 7 Serena Williams moved into the 
quarters. Meanwhile, Jana Novotna, who won the Wimbledon women's 
singles crown in 1998, announced her retirement. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY  
  	   	
</P>
