<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jaguars Keep Third Kicker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- Jaguars coach Tom Coughlin doesn't  
believe in luxuries. That's what made his decision to keep a third 
kicker, Steve Lindsey, so surprising. 
</P>
<P>
	Unable to deny the impact Lindsey had as a kickoff specialist in  
the preseason, Coughlin went against his own instinct, and kept the 
second-year player from Mississippi on the 53-man roster. 
</P>
<P>
	In the matter of six weeks, Lindsey went from a mere extra leg  
at training camp to one of the biggest surprises on the Jaguars 
roster. 
</P>
<P>
	He found out he had made it when his fiancee called up the  
Jaguars internet site Sunday and noticed Lindsey's name was missing 
-- from the list of players who had been waived. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're sitting there, thinking, they've got to cut 17  
people,'' Lindsey said. ``It would be more than easy for them to 
say, `Let's get rid of the kicker.' It came as a total surprise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His impact was hard to deny. The rookie sent 11 of his 18  
kickoffs into the end zone during the preseason. That takes the 
strain off a kickoff coverage unit that has struggled over the 
team's first four years. 
</P>
<P>
	Coughlin was so impressed that he chose to keep a third kicker  
over a ninth defensive back, the number he traditionally carries. 
Veteran cornerback Deon Figures was released and second-year 
cornerback Cordell Taylor, last year's second-round draft pick, was 
traded to the Seattle Seahawks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Lindsey proved himself to be a valuable commodity for this  
team,'' Coughlin said. ``You rank the players to see how well they 
contribute to the team. After considering the roster, you have to 
consider him an important improvement to the defense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lindsey attempted only one field goal in the preseason, although  
he made some long kicks in practice and during pre-game warmups 
that stoked Coughlin's interest. There's a chance the new kicker 
could be used for long field goals. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Jacksonville's other kicker is just one year removed  
from the Pro Bowl. Mike Hollis enters the season having made 13 
consecutive field goals. Kickoff depth has never been his strength, 
however, and his problems are exacerbated by a bad back. He had 
offseason surgery on two ruptured disks that still bother him on 
kickoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``As long as it helps the team out, I'm fine with it,'' Hollis  
said. ``Steve's a great kicker. He deserves a job somewhere. Having 
a guy like that is important for the kickoff coverage. We've tried 
for four years to get it squared away. Hopefully, Steve Lindsey is 
the answer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If he is, Lindsey might have to tinker with his schedule a bit.  
His wedding date is set for Oct. 23. That happens to be the Jaguars 
bye week. 
</P>
<P>
	``If coach let's us, we'll get married then,'' Lindsey said.  
``If not, I guess we'll wait until the end of the season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Either way, it will be better than the way he spent last year.  
After being waived by the San Francisco 49ers before training camp, 
Lindsey returned to Oxford, Miss., where he worked on his kicking 
game and made ends meet by working at a collection agency. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was making people real mad,'' he said. ``It was not where I  
wanted to be. It's good to be back.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
