<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Buckeyes Hold Spirited Practices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- Three months until the game with Michigan  
and four weeks before the first Big Ten game, Ohio State turned 
mean and nasty in practice last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was very intense,'' wide receiver Reggie Germany said of  
the Buckeyes' workouts. ``It was like full go. Tempers were 
flaring. It got exciting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So heated were the exchanges between teammates that Germany said  
he had to take an extra precaution to make sure he didn't get his 
head turned around backwards by friendly fire. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had to put my mouthpiece in for once in practice,'' he said  
with a smile. 
</P>
<P>
	In the wake of a 23-12 Kickoff Classic loss to Miami on Aug. 29,  
Ohio State's practices turned into a survival test. Instead of 
walking through plays in anticipation of Saturday's home opener 
against No. 14 UCLA, the 13th-ranked Buckeyes used the workouts to 
purge themselves of the bad feelings left over from the defeat by 
the Hurricanes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought the kids responded pretty well,'' coach John Cooper  
said of last week's physical sessions. ``What did we get 
straightened out? I hope a lot of things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miami dominated the Buckeyes, outgaining them 398-220 while  
running and passing for more yards. It was Ohio State's first loss 
in a season opener in 12 years. 
</P>
<P>
	When the Hurricanes needed a big play, they got it. They had  
gains of 44, 50, 42, 67 and 23 yards to tilt momentum, field 
position and the scoreboard in their favor. 
</P>
<P>
	They also ground it out when they needed to, eating up 7:39 of  
the fourth quarter on a 79-yard drive that included only nine 
passing yards. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm disappointed in our football team -- not any one area,''  
Cooper said. ``That's not like us to play like we did. We played 
almost like we didn't want to be there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Linebacker Na'il Diggs agreed that the Buckeyes played less than  
spirited football. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was definitely an emotional pitch that wasn't there,''  
he said. ``I definitely saw it when we came back and watched the 
film. It was not a couple of guys, it was everybody. We weren't 
running down the field. We weren't playing hard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked why that was, Diggs said, ``It was a lot of little things  
that threw us off. A lot of the guys just didn't want to be there. 
It was an away game, early in the season against a good team. It 
was a lot of little things that got to us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now the Buckeyes are confronted by UCLA, which opened its season  
with last Saturday's 38-7 victory over Boise State. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not going to win just by showing up,'' Cooper warned.  
``We're anxious to play a game. After you get beat, you like to 
come back the next day and get it out of your system. It's been a 
long 10 days.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bruins are a dangerous opponent because of their firepower,  
Cooper said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've got great offensive skills people,'' he said.  
``They've got three or four of the best wide receivers we'll play 
against. And they've got a stable of running backs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he said Miami's 49-45 upset of previously unbeaten and  
third-ranked UCLA last year gave his players an indication of how 
good the Bruins are. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you don't think they're good on offense, look at what they  
did last year against Miami,'' Cooper said. ``They had 670 yards of 
offense against Miami -- a Miami team that kicked our butts up one 
side and down the other last week.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
