<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> British Olympian Cleared of Charge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Linford Christie, the 1992 Olympic 100-meter  
champion, was cleared Monday of drug charges by British track 
authorities, but he still must await a final ruling by track and 
field's world governing body. 
</P>
<P>
	The UK Athletics panel ruled it ``could not be proved beyond  
reasonable doubt'' that Christie used prohibited substances despite 
traces of the steroid Nandrolone showing in a urine sample he gave 
after a meet in Germany in February. 
</P>
<P>
	Christie, who admitted to being ``bitter'' about the charges,  
said he was delighted at being ``totally exonerated by the 
disciplinary committee.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I was always confident of this outcome having maintained from  
the outset that I had done nothing wrong,'' he said in a statement. 
``I am relieved that the disciplinary committee in their findings 
has shown that they totally support me in this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now, the International Amateur Athletic Federation will consider  
the findings of the UK Athletics investigation before deciding 
whether to take action against the 39-year-old sprinter. 
</P>
<P>
	The UK Athletics panel consisted of the same three members who  
cleared European 200-meter champion Doug Walker of a similar charge 
in July. The Walker decision was subsequently rejected by the IAAF 
and has been sent to an arbitration panel. 
</P>
<P>
	IAAF spokesman Giorgio Reineri said each case is treated  
individually. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not automatic,'' he said of the decision to send a case  
to arbitration. The doping commission will review (the UK 
Athletics' findings) and decide ... whether to recommend to the 
Council to send Christie's case to arbitration. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot jump to conclusions. Maybe Christie brought to the  
attention of the panel (in London) some element we don't know 
about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement, UK Athletics -- the national governing body --  
said the disciplinary committee ``has unanimously decided to 
dismiss the disciplinary proceedings'' and lifted Christie's 
suspension. 
</P>
<P>
	``The disciplinary committee concluded that it could not be  
proven beyond reasonable doubt that the substance present in the 
sample was derived from a prohibited substance,'' the statement 
said. ``Linford Christie has therefore been cleared of all 
charges.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reineri said the case was unusual because Christie is basically  
retired. 
</P>
<P>
	``I understand that this has an impact on (Christie's)  
reputation -- he's been a great champion,'' he said. ``He's not just 
a champion in Britain, he's been a champion of the world. This is 
very important for him and for the IAAF.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Christie, who runs for fun and coaching some British sprinters,  
was suspended after testing positive for Nandrolone after an indoor 
meet in Dortmund, Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	A strong anti-drug campaigner, Christie declared his innocence  
when the result of his test was announced Aug. 4 and vowed to clear 
his name. 
</P>
<P>
	Christie said the testing for Nandrolone was ``flawed.''  
</P>
<P>
	``The IAAF ... should halt all Nandrolone positives until they  
can actually say, `Yes, the testing is reliable, ' '' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
