<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Monday, Sept. 6, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Pro-Indonesians on Rampage  
</P>
<P>
	DILI, Indonesia (AP) -- Tens of thousands of people are fleeing  
East Timor's capital city today as Indonesian soldiers torch homes, 
and terrorize the population with guns and machetes, witnesses say. 
U.N. officials evacuated 300 workers from the provincial capital of 
Dili to Australia. The mayhem follows a U.N.-sponsored referendum a 
week ago in which 78.5 percent of the voters opted to secede from 
Indonesia. The East Timorese International Support Center said more 
than 170 people had been slaughtered by pro-Indonesian militiamen. 

</P>
<P>
	Mubarak Slightly Injured in Attack  
</P>
<P>
	PORT SAID, Egypt (AP) -- Guards shot and killed a man who grazed  
President Hosni Mubarak with a sharp instrument as he drove through 
a northern town today, the government said. Mubarak, who has 
survived three assassination attempts, was slightly injured and the 
wound was treated with a disinfectant. Police identified the 
assailant as Said Hassan Suleiman, a clothing vendor who ``has been 
known for impulsive behavior and recklessness.'' The statement 
added he had ``no political affiliations.'' Mubarak's predecessor, 
Anwar Sadat, was assassinated in 1981. 

</P>
<P>
	Wildfire Threat Hits Calif. Resort  
</P>
<P>
	BIG BEAR LAKE, Calif. (AP) -- Fire officials hope to bring a  
major wildfire under control today. Flames have scorched more than 
63,000 acres in the San Bernardino Mountains. The fire has 
destroyed more than 50 vehicles and at least 19 structures, 
including several homes. The battle against the fire has cost 
nearly $10 million. There has also been a cost to tourism. Shops 
and hotels in the area usually do a brisk business over the Labor 
Day holiday weekend. But this year, the fire kept many people away. 

</P>
<P>
	Greek Orthodox to Pope: Apologize  
</P>
<P>
	ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- Greek Orthodox Church leaders said Pope  
John Paul II must apologize for centuries of perceived Roman 
Catholic misdeeds against the Christian Orthodox to receive a 
religious welcome in Greece. But the Holy Synod's snub was not 
binding on Greek Premier Costas Simitis' government, which has said 
the pontiff can make his first-ever visit to Greece as pope. The 
pope and some Christian Orthodox leaders have expressed a desire to 
draw the two churches closer after a nearly 1,000-year 
estrangement. The pope has expressed a desire to visit Greece this 
year. 

</P>
<P>
	Report: China Dissident Gets 3 Years  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- A political activist in eastern China has been  
sentenced to three years in a labor camp on subversion charges, a 
human rights group said today. Peng Cheng was arrested after 
circulating a petition appealing to the government to reverse its 
official condemnation of 1989 pro-democracy protests, the Hong 
Kong-based Information Center for Human Rights and Democratic 
Movement in China said. Hundreds and possibly thousands of people 
were killed when soldiers shot their way into Beijing on the night 
of June 3, 1989, to break up demonstrations on Tiananmen Square. 

</P>
<P>
	Cambodia Plans Fight Against AIDS  
</P>
<P>
	PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) -- Cambodian officials, seeking ways to  
fend off an HIV epidemic, said today they plan to enforce condom 
use in the nation's commercial sex outlets. Health officials said 
an estimated 100 Cambodians catch the deadly virus each day -- the 
highest infection rate in Asia. Police enforcement of mandatory 
condom-use in brothels has proved in testing to effectively shut 
down Cambodia's most common route of infection, health officials 
said. The sex trade is considered the main link in the spread of 
HIV, with almost half of the country's 20,000 sex workers believed 
to be infected with the killer virus. 

</P>
<P>
	Imported Vehicle Sales Up in Japan  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Sales of imported vehicles rose 3 percent in August  
from the same month last year, an industry association announced 
today. Importers sold a total of 17,086 cars, trucks and buses last 
month, compared with 16,588 sold in August last year, the Japan 
Automobile Importers Association said. The August increase in 
imports followed a 5.9-percent drop last month. The figures come as 
Japan is struggling to emerge from its worst economic downturn in 
50 years. 

</P>
<P>
	Seles Beats Surprising Capriati  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Monica Seles ended Jennifer Capriati's  
surprising run at the U.S. Open tennis tournament with a 6-4, 6-3 
victory today. Seles, a former Open champion, advanced to the 
quarterfinals with the win. Capriati hadn't advanced this far in a 
Grand Slam event since she met Seles in the semifinals of the 1991 
Open. Seles will next face the winner of today's match between No. 
7 Serena Williams and No. 16 Conchita Martinez. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
  	   	
</P>
