<DOCNO> APW19990906.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 05:10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Monday, Sept. 6, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Poll: Co-Workers Want To Lash Out  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- One employee out of six reports being so  
angered by a co-worker in the past year that he or she felt like 
hitting the person -- but didn't, a new poll finds. Workers under 
age 35 and those in clerical, office and sales jobs were the most 
likely to feel like socking somebody, with about 22 percent in each 
of those groups admitting as much. Some 49 percent of the 
respondents to the telephone survey by the Marlin company said they 
generally are at least a little angry at work. But overall stress 
levels among workers are declining. 

</P>
<P>
	Three Serbs Killed in Kosovo Clash  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO said today that Russian  
peacekeepers killed three Serbs after the Serbs disregarded an 
order to stop beating two wounded ethnic Albanians and instead 
started shooting at the Russians, NATO said. A NATO spokesman said 
the Russians were attempting to break up a firefight between the 
Serbs and ethnic Albanians. Ethnic Albanians have accused the 
Russians of favoring the Serbs. NATO insists that Russian troops 
have been evenhanded since they arrived in Kosovo on June 12. 

</P>
<P>
	Man Threatens Mubarak, Is Shot Dead  
</P>
<P>
	PORT SAID, Egypt (AP) -- Security guards shot dead a man who  
threatened Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak with a knife today, 
witnesses said. The president was unhurt. Mubarak was waving to a 
crowd through his car window when the man approached wielding a 
knife, the witnesses said. Mubarak has survived at least three 
attempts on his life. His predecessor, President Anwar Sadat, was 
assassinated in 1981. 

</P>
<P>
	Bid Launched To Save Belfast Accord  
</P>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Former Sen. George Mitchell,  
who helped broker Northern Ireland's peace agreement, is holding 
discussions today with two parties in hopes of salvaging the deal. 
Mitchell is meeting with representatives from the IRA-linked Sinn 
Fein and the Ulster Unionists in a diplomatic effort expected to 
last several weeks. The Ulster Unions, the major Protestant party, 
have refused to form the envisaged four-party Cabinet until the 
Irish Republican Army accepts its obligation to disarm. Sinn Fein 
has refused to disarm. 

</P>
<P>
	Dennis Finally Leaves North Carolina  
</P>
<P>
	BELHAVEN, N.C. (AP) -- The storm called Dennis is finally leaving  
North Carolina after almost two weeks, but in its wake left some 
flood damage and traffic deaths. The National Weather Service says 
Dennis, which twice gained hurricane strength, dumped as much as 
six inches of rain on some areas of North Carolina. Police said 
five people died in traffic accidents on rain-slickened roads. 

</P>
<P>
	Anti-Independence Group Riots in E.Timor  
</P>
<P>
	DILI, Indonesia (AP) -- Pro-Indonesian militiamen set fire to the  
home of an East Timorese Nobel Peace laureate today, and the heads 
of victims were reportedly displayed on sticks outside the capital 
in a rampage following the territory's vote for independence. Days 
of rioting prompted tens of thousands to flee East Timor, and 
Australia launched an airlift to evacuate 200 U.N. elections 
officials from the island. A top U.N. envoy met in Jakarta with the 
Indonesian president amid accusations that Indonesian security 
forces were doing nothing to halt the bloodshed. 

</P>
<P>
	Reports: GM Offers Lifetime Jobs  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- General Motors has reportedly offered a  
guarantee of lifetime employment to many employees as part of 
negotiations over a new contract with the United Automobile Workers 
union. The union's three-year contracts with the major automakers 
are due to expire Sept. 14. Under the existing contracts, workers 
effectively have lifetime employment because the terms bar 
automakers from allowing employment to fall by more than 5 percent 
nationally or in any of a dozen regions. The company's proposal is 
aimed at addressing workers' job security fears while allowing GM 
to reduce overall employment more rapidly, The New York Times 
reported today. 

</P>
<P>
	Japanese Stock Prices Rebound  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices rebounded moderately in thin  
trading today, while the dollar fell against the yen. The Nikkei 
gained 126.52 points to close at 17,756.51. 

</P>
