<HEADLINE> Norway's Shipbuilders Stage Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OSLO, Norway (AP) -- More than 20,000 workers staged a spot  
strike Monday to draw attention to troubles in Norway's shipyard 
industry that they fear could cost thousands of jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	The shipyards, which build both vessels and offshore oil  
platforms, have been hit by slowdowns in both the oil and shipping 
industries.As many as 4,000 people have already been laid off, and 
the industry fears that 15,000-25,000 jobs could disappear in all. 
</P>
<P>
	About 12,000 shipyard workers and 10,000 oil industry employees  
staged a one-hour protest Monday in hopes of pressing the 
government to take steps to stimulate the industry. 
</P>
<P>
	``The supply industry is already in a crisis, and steps are  
being taken too late to save large portions of the industry,'' the 
head of the Norwegian Oil and Petrochemical Workers Union, Lars 
Anders Myhre, was quoted as telling the Norwegian news agency NTB. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, the government said it was considering measures that  
could include tax cuts for offshore oil projects. 
</P>
<P>
	The shipyards have been hit by a general slowdown. The yards  
specializing in offshore oil installations saw hopes of major 
contracts dwindle when companies postponed new projects as oil 
prices plunged to 12-year lows of about $10 per barrel last year. 
</P>
<P>
	However, prices have rebounded, and Norwegian unions said it was  
time for the government to push new projects. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
