<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Monday, Sept. 6, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Indonesia Imposes Martial Law in E. Timor  
</P>
<P>
	DILI, Indonesia (AP) -- Stung by international criticism,  
President B.J. Habibie on Tuesday signed an order imposing martial 
law in East Timor. The Indonesian ruler's decision came as 
thousands of refugees fled Dili, the provincial capital, and 
anti-independence militias continued a wave of terror. World 
leaders urged Indonesia to make good on its pledge to provide 
security in Dili. But witnesses said Indonesian troops were aiding 
the militias and trying to intimidate journalists and U.N. workers 
into fleeing the territory. 

</P>
<P>
	Teachers, Detroit Schools Reach Pact  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Detroit's public school teachers could return to  
the city's classrooms as early as Wednesday after they reached a 
deal today to end a six-day strike over reforms proposed by a new 
chief executive hired to fix the troubled district. The teachers 
struck in defiance of state law, and legislative leaders had said 
they would move to seek sanctions against the teachers tomorrow. 
The district's chief executive, David Adamany, had said lawmakers 
likely would invoke a 1994 law that bars strikes by teachers and 
fines them one day's pay for each day they strike. 

</P>
<P>
	FALN Prisoners To Discuss Clemency  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- Sixteen Puerto Ricans jailed on  
sedition and weapons convictions will hold a conference call 
Wednesday to decide whether to accept President Clinton's offer of 
clemency, supporters said today. The Puerto Rican Pro Human Rights 
Committee, which has led efforts to free the activists, said the 
prisoners would likely announce their decision before the deadline 
of 5 p.m. on Friday. The prisoners are members of the Armed Forces 
for National Liberation and the Macheteros, pro-independence groups 
that between 1974 and 1983 staged more than 130 bomb attacks in the 
United States. The attacks killed six people and injured dozens. 

</P>
<P>
	Afghan Opposition Attacks Taliban  
</P>
<P>
	ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- Afghanistan's northern-based  
opposition attacked the ruling Taliban militia today in two 
northern provinces and captured several strategic posts, an 
opposition spokesman said. No reports of casualties were 
immediately available. There was no immediate comment from the 
Taliban, who rule almost 90 percent of Afghanistan, including the 
capital, Kabul. The opposition controls the remaining 10 percent of 
the country. 

</P>
<P>
	Book Details Pope Pius XII's Anti-Semitism  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A new book says Pope Pius XII's deep  
anti-Semitism contributed to his refusal to condemn Nazi atrocities 
during World War II. Author John Cornwell cites in the book a 
letter written by the pope in 1919 that describes a group of 
revolutionary Jews in Munich, Germany, as ``a gang of young women 
of dubious appearance, Jews like all the rest of them, hanging 
around in all the offices with provocative demeanor and suggestive 
smiles.'' The book, ``Hitler's Pope: The Secret History of Pius 
XII,'' is excerpted in the October issue of Vanity Fair. 

</P>
<P>
	Lewis Hosts Telethon Despite Illness  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Jerry Lewis, who was hospitalized last month  
with viral meningitis, today fought off double vision and headaches 
to host his annual Labor Day Telethon. Lewis appeared last night 
for the first three hours of the event that raises money for the 
Muscular Dystrophy Association. He sang a duet with Martin Short 
and performed another solo. He returned today for the final four 
hours. The telethon raised a record $53.1 million in pledges, 
breaking last year's mark of $51.57 million. Two neurologists 
monitored his condition throughout the broadcast. 

</P>
<P>
	Davenport Advances to Quarterfinals  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Defending U.S. Open champion Lindsay Davenport  
advanced to the quarterfinals tonight, beating Julie Halard-Decugis 
6-1, 6-2. In other action, No. 5 Mary Pierce scored a 6-3, 7-6 
(8-6) victory over Sabine Appelmans and Serena Williams defeated 
Conchita Martinez 4-6, 6-2, 6-2, to join her older sister, Venus in 
the quarterfinals. Monica Seles scored a 6-4, 6-3 victory over 
Jennifer Capriati. Davenport will meet Pierce in the quarterfinal 
duel. 

</P>
<P>
	Indians Edge Orioles 7-6  
</P>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Rookie Alex Ramirez homered and had a  
career-high five RBIs, and Roberto Alomar drove in the tiebreaking 
run in the eighth inning as the Cleveland Indians beat the 
Baltimore Orioles 7-6 today. Manny Ramirez had three hits, 
including two doubles, helping the Indians bounced back from a 3-0 
deficit after they were held to a pair of singles through the first 
six innings. Dave Burba (13-7) allowed three runs, five hits and 
four walks in seven innings to win his fifth straight decision. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LISI de BOURBON  
  	   	
</P>
