<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Assassination Attempts Vs. Mubarak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak succeeded Anwar Sadat, who was  
assassinated by Jihad, an Islamic militant group, in 1981. Since 
then, several assassination attempts have reportedly been made on 
or plotted against Mubarak: 
</P>
<P>
	-- On Monday, a man identified as Said Hassan Suleiman, a clothes  
vendor, approached Mubarak's motorcade in the northern city of Port 
Said and grazed his arm with what appeared to be a knife. 
Presidential security guards killed Suleiman on the spot. 
</P>
<P>
	-- In December 1995, the Interior Ministry confirmed that the  
Jihad group had plotted to ram two explosives-rigged cars into 
Mubarak's car on his way to open a new parliament session that 
month. Police arrested 56 suspects. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Testimony in the trial of Egyptian Sheik Omar Abdel-Rahman in  
New York earlier in 1995 indicated there was a plot to assassinate 
Mubarak during a trip to the United States in 1993. The visit never 
took place. 
</P>
<P>
	-- On June 26, 1995 gunmen opened fire on Mubarak's motorcade in  
the Ethiopian capital, Addis Ababa. Two Ethiopian policemen were 
killed and one was wounded. Relations with Sudan soured after Egypt 
and Ethiopia accused Sudan of having supported the assailants. 
</P>
<P>
	-- In November 1993, newspapers reported that security  
authorities headed off a plot to mine the airport at Sidi Barrani 
on the Mediterranean Sea before Mubarak stopped there en route to a 
meeting with Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi. The government 
confirmed only that there was an attempt on an important official. 
In 1994, two soldiers and a civilian were convicted and executed 
for the plot. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
