<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  5 Arrested in Israel Car Bombings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Declaring that their common task is fighting  
terrorism, Israel and the Palestinians expressed hope Monday that a 
pair of car bombings will not knock the newly revived peace process 
off track. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said five arrests were made in the Sunday bombings in the  
northern Israeli towns of Haifa and Tiberias. Authorities 
maintained a tight veil of secrecy over the identities of those 
taken into custody -- as well as those of the three slain men, 
apparently the bombers. 
</P>
<P>
	A Tiberias court said police requested the gag order because  
they believed the investigation could uncover further, imminent 
attacks being planned. The court ordered the men held another 11 
days and said police were investigating whether Israeli Arabs were 
involved. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Israeli Arab villages of Daburiya and Mashad, wakes were  
held for three men whom relatives said were the ones killed. 
Israeli security sources said DNA samples were taken from relatives 
of the three -- a procedure that has been used in the past to help 
identify the mangled, charred remains of suicide bombers. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Daburiya men are the bombers, it would mark the second  
time in eight days that Israeli Arabs have been involved in terror 
attacks. Last week, an Israeli Arab stabbed to death an Israeli 
couple, saying he wanted to kill Jews. 
</P>
<P>
	The two incidents have raised concern among Israeli Jews who  
nervously watch for any signs that the country's 1 million Arabs 
will turn against the state and come to identify with their 
Palestinian brethren in the West Bank and Gaza Strip. 
</P>
<P>
	Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak has said in the past he would  
halt the peace process in response to terror attacks, but was 
unlikely to do so over Sunday's twin bombings. No bystanders were 
killed, and if the bombers were indeed Israeli Arabs, Barak could 
not hold the Palestinian Authority responsible. 
</P>
<P>
	``If indeed the investigation discovers that this time the  
terrorists were locals, Israel will have to do what it so often 
preaches -- improve its fight against terrorism,'' said a commentary 
in the liberal Haaretz daily. 
</P>
<P>
	The bombs went off just hours after the festive signing of a new  
West Bank land-for-security accord that also charts the course 
toward a permanent peace agreement by September 2000. The signing 
was widely seen as the opening of a new chapter in 
Israeli-Palestinian relations, following three years of deadlock 
under Barak's hawkish predecessor, Benjamin Netanyahu. 
</P>
<P>
	The Palestinian Cabinet formally ratified the agreement Monday  
night, Construction Minister Azzam Ahmad said. Ahmad would not give 
details about the vote, but said several ministers expressed 
reservations about the agreement, particularly over whether Israel 
would fulfill its obligation to relinquish West Bank territory and 
release Palestinian prisoners. 
</P>
<P>
	Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat reacted swiftly to the attacks,  
calling Barak and condemning the bombings. ``Terrorist attacks 
should be combated,'' Arafat said after a meeting Monday with the 
Israeli justice minister, Yossi Beilin. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past, Arafat has come under fire from Israeli leaders for  
not doing enough to rein in Palestinian militants and being too 
slow in condemning violence. However, with Israel on the verge of 
handing another 11 percent of the West Bank to Palestinian control, 
Arafat apparently does not want to do anything to hurt the new 
peace deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Beilin said he believed Arafat was serious about fighting  
terrorism. ``We all understand that terrorism is there to prevent 
us from achieving peace and we won't let it win,'' Beilin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Israeli security forces were placed on high alert, saying there  
was concern that Islamic militants might try to stop the momentum 
in peacemaking with more attacks, especially during the Jewish High 
Holidays, which begin this weekend. The Palestinian movements Hamas 
and Islamic Jihad carried more than a dozen bombings in the past 
five years, killing scores of Israelis. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Monday, Beilin and his Palestinian counterpart, Freih Abu  
Medein, signed an agreement to set up a liaison office to address 
legal grievances from both sides. The move is meant to give both 
Israelis and Palestinians redress on issues ranging from financial 
claims to criminal cases pending before the courts. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
