<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> eBay Removes Baby Sale Offers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Bids for an unborn child reached into six  
figures on the online auction house eBay, less than a week after a 
human kidney received million-dollar offers there. 
</P>
<P>
	Company officials removed listings for three babies on the site  
and believe them all to be hoaxes, Steve Westly, eBay's marketing 
vice president, said Monday. The two earlier kidney sales were also 
thought to be shams. 
</P>
<P>
	While selling humans or their organs is illegal, eBay customers  
appeared interested in both. Bids for one of the children reached 
$109,100, while one of two listed kidneys had fetched a $5.7 
million offer. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the child listings, posted Sunday, offered a boy due to  
be born later this month to two students at the University of 
Chicago law school. It also offered ``intelligence scores of 
parents ... upon request.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Company officials declined to release names of the purported  
baby sellers and would not say whether law-enforcement officials 
are investigating. But Westly said the latest auction likely took 
its cue from the kidney hoax. 
</P>
<P>
	``All of the sudden we see this turn up in the press and we see  
a little flurry,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, the San Jose, Calif.-based eBay banned the  
sale of guns and ammunition after people tried selling a missile, a 
bazooka, a rocket launcher and other military weapons. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
