<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 20:40:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chargers Sign Coveted CB Lewis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Cornerback Darryll Lewis, who was released  
Saturday by the Tennessee Titans, agreed to terms on a two-year 
deal with the San Diego Chargers on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis, going into his ninth NFL season, will receive a $600,000  
signing bonus and a $400,000 salary for this season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chargers have until 1 p.m. Tuesday to clear a roster spot  
for Lewis. They are trying to trade cornerback Dwayne Harper to the 
San Francisco 49ers. If a deal doesn't go through, Harper will be 
released. 
</P>
<P>
	Harper, who signed with the Chargers as an unrestricted free  
agent from Seattle in 1994, wasn't at practice Monday and his 
locker was cleaned out. He met with club officials earlier in the 
day. 
</P>
<P>
	``I haven't been officially released,'' Harper said Monday  
evening. ``I know I can still play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Beathard said club officials ``thanked him for everything he did  
here. Dwayne's been great for us. He got better each preseason 
game, but we got the chance to get Darryll and we had to go that 
way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harper has missed a good deal of the last three seasons due to  
injuries, including the final 15 games last year with a neck injury 
that required offseason surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis intercepted an AFC-high 25 passes over the last five  
years. He played under Chargers defensive backs coach Rod Perry 
when he held the same job with the Oilers from 1995-96, and earned 
a Pro Bowl spot in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis was cut by the Titans because he lost his starting job and  
the $2 million he was due to make is too much to pay a nickel back. 
He was beaten out for the starting job by second-year pro Samari 
Rolle. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
