<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 14:20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Tries Hand at Hand Tools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NORFOLK, Va. (AP) -- Armed with a cordless electric drill,  
President Clinton pitched in briefly Monday to help with some 
renovation work at the 75-year-old Coleman Place Elementary School 
and was reminded he's now a homeowner. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never used one of these,'' the president, wearing a hard hat  
and blue work shirt, remarked as he fastened about eight screws to 
the top of a computer desk. 
</P>
<P>
	Having recently, along with the first lady, purchased a $1.7  
million home in Westchester County, New York, Clinton predicted he 
might need just such a tool. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told her now that I'm a homeowner I'd better get one of  
these,'' said Clinton. ``I've never seen one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president and Hillary Rodham Clinton last Thursday bought  
the 110-year-old Georgian colonial in Westchester County outside 
New York City as Mrs. Clinton establishes residency in New York for 
a probable bid for a Senate seat from the state. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
