<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Share Prices Rebound / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices rebounded moderately in thin  
trading today, while the dollar fell against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed up 126.52  
points, or 0.72 percent, to end the day's trade at 17,756.51. On 
Friday, the average closed down 1.26 points, or 0.01 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 109.62 yen late today, down 0.12 yen from late  
Friday in Tokyo and below its late New York level of 110.05 yen on 
Friday. The greenback traded in a narrow range today in Tokyo, 
posting a high of 109.75 yen and hitting a low of 109.34 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In foreign exchange, the dollar slipped marginally in quiet  
trading as market players awaited the release of Japan's April-June 
gross domestic product data on Sept. 9. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on averages of forecasts given by economists surveyed by  
Dow Jones and Nikkei, GDP is expected to have contracted 0.1 
percent from the previous quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The size of a second supplementary budget to support the economy  
will be determined based on the GDP data, Japanese officials have 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Market watchers say that despite the respite in the dollar's  
recent steady fall against the yen, sentiment for the U.S. currency 
remains weak and that investors are still optimistic about a 
possible economic turnaround developing in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 116.15 yen, down  
from 117.65 late Friday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, Tokyo share prices rose following Friday's  
rise of 235.34 points on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial index closed at 11,078.45 on Friday,  
buoyed by slowing U.S. job growth in August, which eased market 
worries about inflationary pressure. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said investors were awaiting a special quotation for the  
settlement of futures and options contracts on Friday as well as 
the release of the gross domestic product data. 
</P>
<P>
	``If there's a serious shrinkage in GDP, Japan's second  
supplementary budget will expand,'' and that will help stocks, said 
Tsuyosi Nomaguchi, a strategist at Daiwa Securities. He added he 
doesn't expect the data to be very bad. 
</P>
<P>
	As estimated 450 million shares changed hands on the first  
section of the Tokyo Stocks Exchange today, down from 465 million 
shares Friday. Advancers outnumbered decliners 646 to 541, with 149 
unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section closed up 15.08 points, or 1.00 percent, to 1,512.08. 
The TOPIX closed up 0.01 points, insignificant in percentage terms, 
on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 215 10-year Japanese government  
bond fell to 1.8000 percent from Friday's finish of 1.8400 percent, 
driving its price up to 100.84 yen from 100.50 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
