<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wal-Mart Heirs Buy St. Louis Blues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Fresh from a failure to buy a sports empire in  
Denver, Wal-Mart heirs Bill and Nancy Laurie have purchased the St. 
Louis Blues and Kiel Center. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale, which coincided with the opening of the Blues'  
training camp, was announced late Monday afternoon in a statement 
released by the team. Terms of the sale were not immediately 
disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	The purchase caps a months-long effort by the Lauries, a  
Columbia, Mo., couple, to enter the world of professional sports 
ownership, and a nearly year-long effort by the partnership that 
owned the Blues to recoup its investment. In March, the Lauries 
were unsuccessful in their attempt to buy the NHL's Colorado 
Avalanche and the NBA's Denver Nuggets and their new home, the 
Pepsi Center. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nancy and I are looking forward to building on the strong  
Blues hockey tradition in the St. Louis community,'' Bill Laurie 
said in a statement. ``We have been searching for the right sports 
opportunity for several years and, to our delight, we found it 
right down the road.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Laurie planned to meet with the team Tuesday morning, with  
an 11 a.m. (CST) news conference at the Kiel Center to follow. The 
Lauries are the second Columbia entry into the St. Louis sports 
market in recent years; Stan Kroenke is a minority owner of the 
NFL's St. Louis Rams. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lauries were at a movie in Columbia on Monday night, and did  
not immediately return a call to The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lauries' Denver deal fell through when shareholders of  
Ascent Entertainment Group, which owned the sports properties, 
filed suit, claiming the $400 million sale price was as much as 
$150 million too low. An out-of-court settlement resulted in an 
auction. 
</P>
<P>
	Several groups of investors, including one led by former Denver  
Broncos quarterback John Elway, bid on the teams and the arena. The 
winner of that auction, a group headed by Colorado billionaire 
Donald Strum, was then to bid one-on-one against the Lauries. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lauries declined to take part in the $1 million-per-bid  
second auction, and Strum bought Ascent's sport assests for $461 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Kiel Partners, a consortium of local businessmen that owns the  
Blues, announced Dec. 30 that it had hired Goldman Sachs, a New 
York investment bank, to explore the team's financial options. They 
included selling the Blues, selling Kiel Center, bringing an NBA 
team to the city, or overhauling Kiel Center's capital structure, 
which includes $96 million in debt. 
</P>
<P>
	Two months ago, Kiel Parters officially announced that the team  
was for sale. 
</P>
<P>
	The partnership said it pumped more than $70 million into the  
team and Kiel Center over the previous four years to cover 
shortfalls. 
</P>
<P>
	This is the third NHL team to change hands this year. Deals for  
two or three more are pending or in the works. 
</P>
<P>
	Nancy Walton Laurie is the daughter of the late Bud Walton, who  
with his late brother Sam co-founded Wal-Mart. Bill Laurie is a 
former basketball player at Memphis State, and he and his wife own 
Crown Center Farms in Columbia, where they raise quarter horses and 
Appaloosas. 
</P>
<P>
	The couple made the largest single donation to the University of  
Missouri in its history in 1996, offering $10 million toward the 
constuction of a new basketball arena. The donation was withdrawn a 
year later after the Lauries felt the university wasn't make enough 
progress toward its construction. 
</P>
<P>
	Stan Kronke, who is married to Nancy's sister and fellow  
Wal-Mart heir Ann, is a minority owner of the St. Louis Rams. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blues made it to the second round of the playoffs last  
season, losing to the eventual Stanley Cup champion Dallas Stars in 
six games. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
