<DOCNO> APW19990906.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 13:10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Monday, Sept. 6, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Homes Set Afire in E. Timor Capital  
</P>
<P>
	DILI, Indonesia (AP) -- Indonesian troops and pro-Indonesia  
militiamen torched scores of homes -- including that of Nobel Peace 
laureate Bishop Carlos Belo -- and rounded up and deported thousands 
of terrified people from East Timor's capital today. Besieged U.N. 
officials evacuated 300 of the world body's elections workers from 
Dili to Australia. ``The situation in Dili is grim, it borders on 
anarchy with widespread shooting, looting,'' a U.N. spokesman said. 
The mayhem followed a U.N.-sponsored referendum a week ago in which 
78.5 percent of the voters opted to secede from Indonesia. 

</P>
<P>
	Arrests Made in Israel Car Bombings  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israel and the Palestinians expressed hope  
today that two car bombings will not knock the newly revived peace 
process off track. Police said five arrests were made in 
yesterday's bombings in the northern Israeli towns of Haifa and 
Tiberias. Authorities kept the identities of those taken into 
custody secret -- as well as those of the three slain men, 
apparently the bombers. If the men are the bombers, it would mark 
the second time in eight days that Israeli Arabs have been involved 
in terror attacks. Last week, an Israeli Arab stabbed to death an 
Israeli couple, saying he wanted to kill Jews. 

</P>
<P>
	Candid Camera Host Allen Funt Dies  
</P>
<P>
	PEBBLE BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- Allen Funt, the television prankster  
whose ``Candid Camera'' thrived on America's willingness to laugh 
at itself and created a trademark phrase, has died. He was 84. Funt 
died yesterday at his home of complications from the 1993 stroke 
that forced him into retirement. ``Candid Camera,'' which aired off 
and on from 1948 to 1990 with Funt as host, secretly filmed people 
confronted with talking mailboxes or trick coffee cups. ``Smile! 
You're on `Candid Camera!' '' was the victim's tipoff. 

</P>
<P>
	Russians Kill 3 Serbs in Yugoslavia  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- In the bloodiest incident of the  
three-month peacekeeping mission in Kosovo, Russian soldiers today 
killed three Serbs who fired on them after refusing to stop beating 
two ethnic Albanians wounded in a gunbattle. The Russians ordered 
Serbs to stop beating the two wounded ethnic Albanians. Instead, 
the Serbs shot at the Russians, who returned fire, killing three of 
them, NATO said. There were no Russian casualties. It was the 
deadliest incident so far involving peacekeepers and Kosovo 
civilians. 

</P>
<P>
	Pakistan School Apparent Bomb Target  
</P>
<P>
	KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) -- Two bombs injured 11 people, mostly  
students, in southern Pakistan in an apparent attack on a Sunni 
Muslim religious school, police said. Minutes after a bomb exploded 
outside the Ashraf-ul-Madaris religious school in Karachi, a second 
bomb ripped through a nearby school bus as teen-age students were 
preparing to board to return home. No one took immediate 
responsibility for the explosions. Police believe the two 
explosions likely targeted the school and its students, who are 
Sunni Muslims. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Assails GOP Tax Plan  
</P>
<P>
	NORFOLK, Va. (AP) -- President Clinton again criticized the  
Republican-passed tax cut plan, saying it would steal money from 
desperately needed school construction programs. About a third of 
American public schools, or 25,000 buildings, need extensive repair 
or replacement, according to the General Accounting Office. The GAO 
also calculated that $112 billion is needed just to repair existing 
schools. The administration claims Republicans' $792 billion tax 
cut program almost ignores school needs in favor of tax breaks for 
the wealthy. 

</P>
<P>
	Reports: GM Offers Lifetime Jobs  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- General Motors Corp. has offered a guarantee of  
lifetime employment to many employees as part of negotiations for a 
new contract with the United Automobile Workers, a newspaper 
reported today. The union's three-year contracts with the major 
automakers are due to expire Sept. 14. Under existing contracts, 
workers effectively have lifetime employment because the terms bar 
automakers from allowing employment to fall by more than 5 percent 
nationally or in any of a dozen regions. Under GM's proposal, the 
lifetime offer would cover current workers with more than 10 years' 
experience, The New York Times reported. 

</P>
<P>
	Sammy Sosa Hits 58th Home Run  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Sammy Sosa hit his major league leading 58th  
homer today, giving him a four-homer lead over Mark McGwire. Sosa 
drove a 2-1 third-inning pitch from Cincinnati's Juan Guzman over 
the left-field wall and onto Waveland Avenue. Sosa is six games 
ahead of his pace during his 66-homer season last year. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY  



  	   	
</P>
