<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FALN Prisoners To Discuss Clemency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- Sixteen Puerto Ricans jailed on  
sedition and weapons convictions will hold a conference call 
Wednesday to decide whether to accept President Clinton's offer of 
clemency, supporters said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Puerto Rican Pro Human Rights Committee, which has led  
efforts to free the activists, said the prisoners would likely 
announce their decision before the deadline of 5 p.m. on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think very soon we will know what course they will take,''  
said Luis Nieves Falcon, spokesman for the committee, during a news 
conference in San Juan. 
</P>
<P>
	The prisoners are members of the Armed Forces for National  
Liberation and the Macheteros, pro-independence groups that between 
1974 and 1983 staged more than 130 bomb attacks in the United 
States. The attacks killed six people and injured dozens. 
</P>
<P>
	None of the prisoners have been convicted in connection with any  
of the bomb attacks, but the offer has infuriated Congressional 
Republicans and law enforcement agencies, who say the prisoners are 
dangerous terrorists. 
</P>
<P>
	They accused Clinton of making the offer in order to win Puerto  
Rican votes for his wife in New York, where she is expected to run 
for Senate. Mrs. Clinton has since disavowed the offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Until last week, the Pro Human Rights Committee said that the  
conditions attached to Clinton's clemency were unacceptable. But on 
Monday it softened its stance, saying it would not condemn any 
prisoner who accepted the offer. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a personal decision, and whatever they choose, we will  
respect it,'' Nieves Falcon said. 
</P>
<P>
	To receive clemency, the prisoners would have to renounce  
violence and abide by parole regulations that include avoiding 
people with criminal records. 
</P>
<P>
	The prisoners complain that the latter limits their right to  
meet with fellow activists, since many radical pro-independence 
leaders have criminal records. 
</P>
<P>
	Deadina Ortiz, the mother of prisoner Elizam Escobar, said  
Monday she has a room prepared for him and hopes he accepts the 
offer. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's time that he were home in my house,'' she said. ``I  
respect whatever decision he makes, but my desire is that he come 
home.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
