<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Serrano Nixes Mrs. Clinton Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Angered by Hillary Rodham Clinton's statements  
opposing clemency for imprisoned Puerto Rican nationalists, Rep. 
Jose Serrano said he would no longer encourage the first lady to 
run for fellow Democrat Daniel Patrick Moynihan's U.S. Senate seat. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm rescinding my encouragement of her candidacy,'' Serrano  
said in today's New York Times. ``Because to me, this is as 
important as Ireland is to the Irish, Israel is to the Jews.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton, who has not yet declared her candidacy for the  
Democratic nomination, said Saturday that President Bill Clinton's 
offer of clemency for 16 FALN members should be withdrawn because 
they have not renounced violence. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clintons have come under fire from Republican critics and  
some law enforcement officials who claimed the president's clemency 
offer was aimed at helping his wife garner votes among New York's 
1.3 million Puerto Ricans. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton's statements caused reactions of anger and  
amazement among several Puerto Rican leaders here, but none more 
than the Puerto Rican-born Serrano. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an action that will make people go out and make sure  
that she's not our next senator,'' Serrano told the Times. ``Maybe 
it's time to go out and find out who else is interested.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Serrano's office was closed for the Labor Day holiday on Monday  
and he could not immediately be reached for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Three other Puerto Rican officials -- State Assemblyman Ruben  
Diaz Jr., City Councilman Jose Rivera and Bronx Borough President 
Fernando Ferrer -- did not go as far as Serrano in threatening to 
pull their support but expressed disappointment. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's disheartening to see her take this position,'' Diaz said.  
``I hope that they don't think that Puerto Ricans are automatically 
going to come out and vote for her just because she is a Democrat. 
I think there needs to be some dialogue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During the 1970s and 1980s the FALN -- the Spanish initials for  
Armed Forces of National Liberation -- was involved in more than 100 
bombings that killed six and wounded dozens more. 
</P>
<P>
	The imprisoned nationalists were not involved in any deaths.  
They were convicted on charges of seditious conspiracy and 
possession of weapons and explosives. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for the nationalists have until 5 p.m. Friday to respond  
in writing to the president's clemency offer. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
