<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 10:50:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> States Press HMOs To Pay On Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	After several months of phone calls and letters trying to  
collect thousands of dollars from Horizon Blue Cross and Blue 
Shield of New Jersey, Dr. Anthony Musarra was getting frustrated. 
</P>
<P>
	Late payments from the health maintenance organization were  
forcing the Absecon, N.J., internist to go further into debt to pay 
his office expenses. So he asked state officials for help. 
</P>
<P>
	New Jersey regulators found they had complaints from more than a  
dozen doctors accusing the HMO of lateness in paying claims. On 
June 15, the state warned Horizon it could be fined up to $10,000 
for appropriate claims not paid within 60 days. 
</P>
<P>
	Within days, Musarra said, checks from Horizon began arriving  
and the HMO apologized for the delay. 
</P>
<P>
	After years watching the escalating feud between HMOs and  
doctors and hospitals, states are becoming more aggressive in 
making sure that plans pay claims. Many states have passed laws to 
specify how quickly HMOs must make payments, and they're issuing 
warnings to plans that don't comply. States including New York, 
Florida, North Carolina and Louisiana have started handing out 
fines. 
</P>
<P>
	``When it goes to the state, the plan gets worried and does  
something about it,'' Musarra said. 
</P>
<P>
	Regulators say they're acting to protect patients. They note  
some health providers illegally bill patients when an HMO balks at 
paying. And patients could be hurt if hospitals or doctors curtail 
services because of financial problems resulting from claim 
disputes. 
</P>
<P>
	Barbara Murray, of Port Charlotte, Fla., said bill collectors  
sent by doctors and hospitals hounded her late husband as he was 
dying of heart disease. The Murrays expected his HMO, Physician 
Corp. of America (since purchased by Humana), to cover his medical 
bills. The health plan resisted, saying the Murrays had not paid 
their premiums on time, a charge the couple disputed. 
</P>
<P>
	``The last time I took him to the hospital he asked me to sue  
them, but I never did,'' said Ms. Murray, who eventually paid some 
of the bills herself. J.C. Murray died in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	HMO industry officials, which defend their record in paying  
claims on time, say they're not surprised that more states are 
closely scrutinizing claims payment, because government agencies 
already regulate what services the plans must cover and how much 
they can increase premiums. 
</P>
<P>
	``States are getting more into the micromanagement of health  
plans in a lot of areas,'' said Susan Pisano, spokeswoman for the 
American Association of Health Plans. 
</P>
<P>
	HMO officials say doctors and hospitals often make mistakes in  
filling out claims, or send them in late, and that's what often 
delays payment. 
</P>
<P>
	Fred Hillman, spokesman for Horizon Blue Cross and Blue Shield,  
said the company denies New Jersey regulators' allegations about 
late payments. He noted the company pays 30 million claims a year, 
and only a few thousand are in dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	Eight states -- Florida, Minnesota, Nevada, North Carolina,  
Colorado, Pennsylvania, Vermont and Virginia -- have passed laws in 
1999 requiring HMOs to pay bills within a certain time or face 
penalties or fines, according to the National Conference of State 
Legislatures. In all, 28 states now have HMO prompt-payment bills, 
most approved in the past three years. 
</P>
<P>
	While hospital executives and doctors are pleased to have the  
states on their side, they say the fines are too small to have much 
impact. 
</P>
<P>
	``Getting fined $1,000, what's that do to a large corporation?''  
said Sarah Smith, of the Greater New York Hospital Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Clifford Sales, a Westfield, N.J.,surgeon, said he's  
struggled for years to get HMOs to pay on time. He contends HMOs 
purposely withhold money to increase profits. 
</P>
<P>
	``When my wife called the plumber, he doesn't leave without  
getting paid, but with HMOs, we are forced to wait and wait and 
wait,'' said Sales, who this year filed a complaint with New Jersey 
regulators, citing about $52,000 in overdue claims from Oxford 
Health Plans. ``I'm glad the state takes an interest, but I'm not 
sure it will help.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Oxford, whose claims-paying ability has come under scrutiny in  
New York and New Jersey, acknowledges it had problems paying bills 
on time a year ago, but has resolved them. It said New York and New 
Jersey regulators have pursued the company because Oxford has the 
most members in the region. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of our physicians say they are being paid promptly,''  
said spokeswoman Francesca Trainor. 
</P>
<P>
	Oxford has paid $71,100 in fines this year to the New York  
Insurance Department for lateness in paying claims. Oxford and 
Aetna U.S. Healthcare, which has paid $15,900 in penalties, have 
accounted for the bulk of the violations in the state. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida, meanwhile, fined six HMOs this summer for denying  
payment to hospitals and doctors for treatment of people in 
emergency rooms, or taking too long to pay emergency department 
bills. Wellcare HMO was fined $80,000, the biggest penalty 
assessed. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
