<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> eBay Removes Baby Sale Offers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Less than a week after a kidney was  
offered on the online auction site eBay, at least three listings of 
babies for sale were posted on the Web site. 
</P>
<P>
	All appeared to be hoaxes and were taken down, Steve Westly,  
eBay's marketing vice president, said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	One posting, offering a baby boy, drew a high bid of $109,100.  
</P>
<P>
	The seller purported to offer a boy, due to be born later this  
month, who would be the child of two law students at the University 
of Chicago. The posting also offered ``intelligence scores of 
parents ... upon request.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Selling children is illegal. The company would not say whether  
law-enforcement officials were investigating. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at eBay said they believe the postings were at least  
partially inspired by the kidney offering, in which a Florida man 
received bids of up to $5.6 million. eBay said that was also 
probably a prank. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, San Jose-based eBay banned the sale of guns  
and ammunition on the site, after people tried selling a missile, a 
bazooka, a rocket launcher and other military weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
