<CATEGORY> weather </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Rain and thunderstorms continued in the East on Labor Day, with  
dry skies in much of the Midwest and West. 
</P>
<P>
	The remnants of Dennis migrated slowly north across North  
Carolina and Virginia. Showers and thunderstorms stretched from 
eastern North Carolina to Virginia into West Virginia and Maryland. 
</P>
<P>
	The Outer Banks of North Carolina received 10 to 20 inches of  
rain between Sunday morning and Monday afternoon. Many rivers and 
streams were overflowing. 
</P>
<P>
	A cold front extended from east of Michigan into Indiana and  
Kentucky, keeping most areas fair to partly cloudy. But an inch and 
a half of rain fell at Detroit Metropolitan Airport, flooding a 
concourse, delaying flights and stranding about 500 passengers 
overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the Southeast was fair and dry, with the exception of  
Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Northern Texas received scattered showers. Conditions were fair  
and dry in the West. 
</P>
<P>
	The high in the lower 48 states was 104 degrees in Palm Springs,  
Calif. The low was 30 in Leadville, Colo. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
