<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MIAs Top U.S. Concerns in Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HANOI, Vietnam (AP) -- Four small wooden boxes holding what are  
believed to be the remains of U.S. soldiers killed during the 
Vietnam War were loaded aboard a Hawaii-bound transport plane for 
the next phase of what Secretary of State Madeleine Albright on 
Tuesday called ``the emotionally brutal'' process of trying to 
identify the war dead. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright and U.S. Ambassador Pete Peterson were among a small  
group of Vietnamese officials and journalists who attended the 
repatriation ceremony on the tarmac at Hanoi International Airport. 
The suspected remains are being flown to a lab in Hawaii where they 
will be compared with DNA of missing soldiers. 
</P>
<P>
	``The work of recovering remains is emotionally brutal, and  
there is no guarantee of success,'' Albright told the crowd. ``But 
we persevere in this intensive effort because the United States 
will never forget our fallen, and our missing, and the sacrifice of 
their families.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Albright has made it clear during her two-day stopover in  
Vietnam that accounting for American MIAs is the United States' top 
priority in Vietnam. She also spoke about the importance of trade 
and economic issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright, who heads later Tuesday to the Asia Pacific Economic  
Cooperation summit in New Zealand, told a news conference in Hanoi 
that she is grateful for Vietnamese cooperation in tracking down 
and recovering the remains of former U.S. soldiers. 
</P>
<P>
	The remains flown out of Vietnam Tuesday were uncovered during  
the most recent of the five joint U.S.-Vietnam digs that are held 
each year. 
</P>
<P>
	``This issue remains paramount to the United States,'' Albright  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cooperation on the MIA issue is one of the bright spots in the  
relationship between Washington and Hanoi that has developed since 
normalization of relations began in 1995, 20 years after the end of 
the Vietnam war. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to excavating suspected plane crash or battle sites,  
U.S. officials have been providing their Vietnamese counterparts 
with access to U.S. military records to help track down the remains 
of the estimated 200,000 Vietnamese MIAs. 
</P>
<P>
	Vietnam's assistance has directly led to steady progress in  
other areas, particularly as the poor communist country seeks to 
develop its economy. Caught in the fallout from the Asian financial 
crisis, Vietnam's economic reforms have slowed to a crawl in the 
last two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials have been moving quickly in recent months to conclude  
a bilateral trade agreement between Vietnam and the United States 
that is expected to mean hundreds of millions of dollars in trade 
and investment in the Southeast Asian country and possibly paving 
the way for its accession to the World Trade Organization. 
</P>
<P>
	The subject came up with every official Albright spoke to  
Monday: Prime Minister Phan Van Khai, Communist Party chief Le Kha 
Phieu and Foreign Minister Nguyen Manh Cam. 
</P>
<P>
	``We spent a great deal of time in all the meetings today on the  
importance of the trade agreement,'' Albright told a news 
conference, adding that she was hopeful of signing a final deal at 
the APEC summit. That would send it to both countries' legislatures 
for approval. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials traveling with Albright said negotiators also  
were on the verge of a number of other agreements, including 
export-import bank assistance, aviation code-sharing, and 
cooperation in science and technology. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright told Phieu that she has seen many changes since her  
first visit two years ago, but later added that much remained to be 
done to help a country plagued by a debt-ridden financial system, 
conflicting laws and widespread corruption. 
</P>
<P>
	``The pace of economic reform is not as rapid or as steady as we  
would like,'' Albright said. 
</P>
<P>
	She said Vietnam was ``denying itself benefits'' that would come  
with improving its international standing by dealing with 
human-rights issues. 
</P>
<P>
	In turn, Vietnamese reporters grilled Albright about America's  
human-rights record, raising the investigation into the siege of 
the Branch Davidian compound in Waco, Texas, U.S. involvement in 
Kosovo and the status of American Indians. 
</P>
<P>
	The Vietnamese also raised the issue of Agent Orange -- the toxic  
defoliant that was widely used by U.S. forces during the Vietnam 
war -- and which has been blamed for a number of illnesses and birth 
defects, U.S. officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	One official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Albright  
thought there should be joint research on Agent Orange before any 
talk of U.S. contributions to funds for reported victims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
