<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 10:10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Flyers' Ron Hextall Retiring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VOORHEES, N.J. (AP) -- Ron Hextall is retiring from hockey,  
ending a career in which he led the Philadelphia Flyers to the 
Stanley Cup 12 years ago when he was the league's best goalie. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement was to come today at a news conference at the  
Flyers' training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	The 35-year-old goalie was released by the Flyers this summer  
after playing backup all season. He was not claimed in the 
expansion draft and his retirement was expected. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be nice if we could keep him in the organization,''  
general manager Bob Clarke said this summer. ``We like Ron a lot. 
We just feel that it's time for a young goaltender to start 
developing with the Flyers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The team waived Hextall July 1, and since no team claimed him  
the Flyers must buy out the final year of his contract. It is 
unclear whether he might be offered a job in the front office or as 
an assistant. 
</P>
<P>
	He was 10-7-4 with a 2.53 goals-against average last season and  
has a 296-214-69 career record. The Atlanta Thrashers, wanting 
younger and less expensive players, did not select him in the 
expansion draft. 
</P>
<P>
	A 13-year veteran, Hextall backed up John Vanbiesbrouck last  
year, overtaking Bernie Parent for the team lead with 240 
victories. Hextall also is No. 1 on the Flyers' career lists for 
games, playoff games and playoff victories. He was the starting 
goalie for the Wales Conference in the 1988 All-Star game. 
</P>
<P>
	Hextall was drafted by the Flyers in 1982, then traded to Quebec  
in the seven-player deal in which the Flyers acquired Eric Lindros 
on June 20, 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	The Flyers traded Hextall, Peter Forsberg, Steve Duchesne, Kerry  
Huffman, Mike Ricci, Chris Simon, a first-round draft pick and $15 
million to the Nordiques for Lindros. 
</P>
<P>
	Hextall was later traded to the New York Islanders, playing one  
season before being dealt back to the Flyers in 1994. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
