<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 15:10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Padres' Nevin Revitalizes Career </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Phil Nevin has finally replaced Ken Caminiti at  
third base. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, it was supposed to have happened 4 1/2 seasons ago in  
Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Nevin's roundabout career, which has included three  
trades and a big attitude adjustment, has been revived at the hot 
corner in San Diego. 
</P>
<P>
	While the Padres stagger along in their lost season, Nevin, the  
top pick overall in the June 1992 draft, grabbed onto what he knew 
was probably his last chance to be an everyday player. 
</P>
<P>
	When George Arias couldn't handle the job as Caminiti's  
replacement in San Diego's post-World Series retooling, it was 
given to Nevin. He responded with 10 homers and 31 RBIs in August, 
stats that compare to his best previous season. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's kind of taken a while, but I guess it's come full  
circle,'' Nevin said at the end of his hot August. ``It's like 
going back home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nevin cautions that it's just been a month. But, said general  
manager Kevin Towers, ``I'd have to say we found ourselves a third 
baseman.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Padres think so much of Nevin that on Monday they were  
finalizing a $2.5 million, two-year contract with an option that 
would pay him $2.6 million in 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	The Padres acquired Nevin from Anaheim in spring training  
because they needed a third catcher. Now Towers envisions Nevin 
bridging the gap at third until acclaimed prospect Sean Burroughs -- 
son of former AL MVP Jeff Burroughs -- comes up. Even after that, 
Nevin can play another position. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevin, who also took over the cleanup spot, is hitting .274 with  
a team-high 72 RBIs. He's second with 22 homers. 
</P>
<P>
	It's been a long climb back for Nevin, who just three years ago  
found himself all the way down in Double-A, learning how to catch. 
</P>
<P>
	With the exception of the events surrounding the replacement  
spring training of 1995, Nevin blames no one but himself. In just a 
few years he went from being big man on campus at Cal State 
Fullerton to an angry young man who fumed every time he made an 
out. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevin, 28, knows why he didn't stick in the big leagues earlier.  
</P>
<P>
	``I was too immature to realize the true joy of playing in the  
major leagues. I took it for granted,'' he said. ``I did nothing to 
deserve being a major league player. I'm very glad I went through 
those times, because there's no way I'd be doing what I'm doing now 
if I hadn't gone through that. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was spoiled,'' he said. ``To be honest, things came easy.''  
</P>
<P>
	After being drafted by Houston, Nevin saw no reason why he  
couldn't quickly become a superstar. After all, in 1992 he won the 
Golden Spikes Award as the nation's top amateur player, was named 
MVP of the College World Series even though the Titans lost the 
championship game, and started for the U.S. Olympic team. 
</P>
<P>
	After two years at Triple-A, reality buzzed him like a knockdown  
pitch. 
</P>
<P>
	Caminiti went to the Padres in a 12-player trade in December  
1994, apparently giving Nevin a shot at the job. With the players' 
strike still under way, the Astros wanted Nevin to play in the 
spring replacement games. He refused and was sent home. 
</P>
<P>
	He started the season back at Triple-A and was still there when  
the strike ended. 
</P>
<P>
	``I definitely was punished because I wasn't a replacement  
player,'' Nevin said. ``I still don't understand that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When he was called up that June he hit .117 in 18 games.  
</P>
<P>
	By then, Nevin had become well-known as a ``snap artist.'' In  
Triple-A, he needed 18 stitches in one hand after trying to rip a 
water fountain off a wall. Another time, he threw a bat into the 
rack so hard that bounced back out, hitting him in the face. 
</P>
<P>
	Padres teammate Dave Magadan, who was platooning at third for  
the Astros in 1995, remembers Nevin's temper. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think he was living and dying with every at-bat instead of  
just getting his feet wet,'' Magadan said. ``If he got a hit he was 
OK, but if he made an out, he'd snap.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nevin has learned to temper his temper, although he did trash a  
dugout restroom in Philadelphia earlier this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're going to make outs,'' he said. ``There are right times  
to do it and wrong times to do it and I was doing it constantly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The last fit Nevin threw with the Astros was a profanity-laced  
tantrum in front of general manager Bob Watson and manager Terry 
Collins when he was demoted in July 1995. Five weeks later he was 
traded to Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevin said the best thing that happened was going down to Class  
AA Jacksonville in 1996 to learn how to catch. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that kind of woke me up,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Once with the Padres, Nevin hit it off with manager Bruce Bochy,  
who gave him his share of at-bats even before he became the 
starter. 
</P>
<P>
	``I look at it like I've got a lot to prove still,'' Nevin said.  
``There's no way I'd ever do anything to let that man down because 
of the chance he's given me that I feel no one else has. '' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
