<DOCNO> APW19990906.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 15:50:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Thrashers Counting on Goalie Rhodes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Damian Rhodes flicked away one shot with  
his pad. Another deflected off his blocker. Finally, he sprawled to 
the ice to cover a loose puck. 
</P>
<P>
	It didn't take long -- just a few minutes into his first  
scrimmage of training camp -- for Rhodes to get a glimpse of how 
frantic things will be with the Atlanta Thrashers. 
</P>
<P>
	He doesn't mind a bit.  
</P>
<P>
	``I like the idea of getting work,'' Rhodes said Monday.  
</P>
<P>
	That's what the Thrashers were hoping when they acquired Rhodes  
from the Ottawa Senators shortly before the NHL expansion draft, 
making him the answer to an inevitable trivia question: Who was the 
first Atlanta player? 
</P>
<P>
	First-year teams never have much scoring, but a stingy goalie  
can transform losses into ties, ties into wins. Just ask the 
Florida Panthers, who reached the Stanley Cup finals in their third 
season on the strength of John Vanbiesbrouck's stellar play. 
</P>
<P>
	``You want to have one go-to guy,'' Thrashers coach Curt Fraser  
said. ``A guy like Rhodes can carry the load.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rhodes is pleased to be in Atlanta after going through a  
roller-coaster of emotions in Ottawa, where he shared the job with 
Ron Tugnutt last season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senators had the second-best record in the Eastern  
Conference but were upset in the first round of the playoffs by 
Buffalo in a four-game sweep. Rhodes and Tugnutt played two games 
apiece. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought we had a real good team,'' Rhodes said. ``But  
something wasn't right. We didn't seem to jell like we were 
supposed to. I'm happy to be out of there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two goalies got along fine, but Rhodes made it clear he  
doesn't miss Ottawa coach Jacques Martin. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were games when Jacques wouldn't tell us who was playing  
until the day of the game,'' Rhodes recalled. ``Every day, we would 
be sitting around wondering what he was going to say. It's nice not 
to have to deal with that anymore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He got the bulk of the work in Ottawa the two previous seasons,  
playing 50 games each year but leaving plenty of work for Tugnutt. 
</P>
<P>
	``As I began to play more, I got better,'' Rhodes said. ``I got  
a lot more confident with my game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That changed last season, when Rhodes played in 45 games with a  
2.44 goals-against average, while Tugnutt worked in 43 games, made 
the All-Star game and led the league with a 1.79 GAA. 
</P>
<P>
	``We kept each other sane,'' Rhodes said. ``Sometimes, we would  
try to guess who was going to play the next game. No matter who we 
picked, we were always wrong. So we stopped doing that after 20 
games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rhodes' impatience in Ottawa is easy to understand. A native of  
Minnesota who grew up as a fan of the North Stars, he was a 
sixth-round draft pick of the Toronto Maple Leafs in 1987. 
</P>
<P>
	After spending three years at Michigan Tech and three more in  
the American Hockey League, he finally made it to the NHL to stay 
in 1993. Even then, Rhodes was stuck behind Felix Potvin, playing 
only 46 games in 2 1/2 seasons before being traded to Ottawa in 
January 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	One good thing about Toronto: Rhodes met his wife, Lara, who  
lived two floors below him in a high-rise apartment building. 
</P>
<P>
	``She saw me walking through the lobby and asked the security  
guard to set us up,'' he said. ``He wound up speaking at our 
wedding. She'll deny it, but that's the way it happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His wife, an actress, has a role in an upcoming horror movie,  
``Pinata.'' Rhodes accompanied her to California over the summer 
for the filming. 
</P>
<P>
	Although he is moving from one of the league's top teams to one  
that figures to be among the worst, Rhodes believes his long-term 
prospects are better in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	The Thrashers are owned by media giant Time-Warner, while the  
Senators are a small-market Canadian team struggling to compete 
financially despite a new arena and sellout crowds. 
</P>
<P>
	Ottawa lost its general manager two years in a row and is  
embroiled in several contract disputes, most notably with star 
center Alexei Yashin. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've got to scratch and claw for everything they get,''  
Rhodes said. ``I knew this would happen. They've been able to get 
all these good players, but now they can't afford them. They're 
kind of like the Montreal Expos of hockey.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although Rhodes turned 30 in May, he's not old by goaltending  
standards. 
</P>
<P>
	``Goalies usually mature later than other players,'' Thrashers  
general manager Don Waddell said. ``You see a lot of them begin to 
come into their own in their late 20s or early 30s. Nothing is 
guaranteed, but he wants to be the workhorse.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
