<DOCNO> APW19990906.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 13:22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> World Stocks Mostly Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The U.S. dollar was mixed against major world currencies Monday,  
while stocks in Asia and Europe were mostly higher and gold prices 
rose. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. markets were closed Monday for the Labor Day holiday.  
</P>
<P>
	The dollar slipped to 109.58 Japanese yen in London from 110.22  
late Friday. Earlier in Tokyo, the dollar finished trading at 
109.62 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar, which traded above 124 yen as recently as May, ended  
last week in New York at 110.05 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Market watchers in Japan said sentiment for the dollar remains  
weak and that investors are still optimistic about a possible 
economic turnaround developing in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro, the single currency of 11 European nations, fell to  
$1.0593 in London on Monday from $1.0600 Friday, but the British 
pound was quoted at $1.6047, up from $1.6040. 
</P>
<P>
	Britian's foreign secretary, Robin Cook, gave a strong  
endorsement to the euro in a speech to Japanese business leaders in 
Tokyo. But Cook did not abandon the British government's 
``wait-and-see'' approach to joining the single currency. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the euro has gained acceptance on world bond markets and  
brought new strength to the economies that have adopted the 
currency. Cook also said a decision to join the euro would be 
subject to support by Britons. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, stock market activity around the world got a boost  
from Wall Street's gains on Friday, when a noninflationary 
employment report ignited a powerful rally. The Dow Jones 
industrial average closed up 2.2 percent Friday and the Nasdaq 
composite index rose nearly 4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Most Asian stock markets closed higher.  
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose  
126.52 points, or 0.72 percent, to end Monday's session at 
17,756.51. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading was light as U.S. markets were closed and as Japanese  
market players awaited the release Thurday of Japan's April-June 
gross domestic product data. The figures are expected to show GDP 
contracted 0.1 percent from the previous quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, the blue chip Hang Index rose 206.85 points, or  
1.6 percent, closing at 13,385.16. South Korean shares also closed 
sharply higher. The main Korea Composite Stock Price Index rose 
32.60 points, or 3.6 percent, to 943.22. 
</P>
<P>
	Bucking the trend was the Jakarta Stock Exchange, where  
Indonesia's key index slumped more than 4 percent because of 
mounting violence in East Timor. 
</P>
<P>
	In London, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index  
was up 43.6 points, or 0.7 percent, at 6,375.7. 
</P>
<P>
	``Markets are looking principally at the strength of demand in  
the States and at prices,'' said Paul Horne, European equity market 
economist at Salomon Smith Barney in London. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 592 European companies rose 2.95  
points, or 0.9 percent, to close at 315.27 Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Germany's Xetra DAX index rose 1.2 percent, Milan's MIBtel index  
was up 0.7 percent, and Amsterdam's AEX index gained 1.5 percent. 
The Paris CAC-40 index closed with a drop of 0.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold dealers in London fixed a recommended price of $254.50 per  
troy ounce, up from $254.00 on Friday. Gold rose 70 cents in Hong 
Kong to close at $255.15 an ounce. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.13 bid per troy ounce, unchanged.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
