<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> `Sixth Sense' Soars at Box Office / Box Office  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- ``The Sixth Sense'' remained the top  
box-office draw for the fifth straight weekend with a 
record-breaking take for the four-day Labor Day weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sixth Sense,'' starring Bruce Willis in the tale of a boy  
who's a magnet for the walking dead, took in $28.5 million, 
according to industry estimates Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	That's nearly as much as the grosses for the rest of the top  
five films, which took in a combined $30.1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never really seen a film at this time of year performing  
so consistently and in such a big way,'' said Paul Dergarabedian, 
president of Exhibitor Relations Co. Inc., which tracks the box 
office. ``It's become one of those films like `Titanic' or `Phantom 
Menace' or `Forrest Gump' that just totally capture the imagination 
of movie-goers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Disney, the film's distributor, again revised its expectations  
for the film, now up to a minimum final gross of $250 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's mind-boggling to think how good this picture's playing,''  
said Chuck Viane, head of distribution for Disney. 
</P>
<P>
	Only one new movie, the Skeet Ulrich-Cuba Gooding Jr. thriller  
``Chill Factor,'' cracked the top 10 this weekend, grossing $5.7 
million for sixth place. ``Runaway Bride'' was No. 2 with $8.6 
million, ``The 13th Warrior'' was third with $8.4 million, 
``Bowfinger'' was fourth with $7 million, and ``The Thomas Crown 
Affair'' was fifth with $6.1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The weekend's other major opening, ``Outside Providence,'' was  
in 11th place with $3.2 million. The coming-of-age comedy was 
unable to capitalize on the track record of writers Peter and Bobby 
Farrelly, who made ``There's Something About Mary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Overall box office figures will top $100 million for the  
weekend, breaking the previous Labor Day record of $96 million in 
1997. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a fitting end to a record summer movie season. The movie  
industry did about $3 billion in business from Memorial Day weekend 
through Labor Day, topping the previous high of $2.6 billion in 
summer 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sixth Sense'' continues to climb the list of Disney's  
highest-grossing movies. The movie will easily pass Disney's No. 2 
picture, ``Aladdin'' with $217 million, and has a shot at beating 
the studio's all-time biggest film, ``The Lion King'' with $312 
million, Viane said. 
</P>
<P>
	Estimated grosses for Friday through Monday at North American  
theaters, according to Exhibitor Relations Co. Inc. Final figures 
are to be released Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	1. ``The Sixth Sense,'' $28.5 million.  
</P>
<P>
	2. ``Runaway Bride,'' $8.6 million.  
</P>
<P>
	3. ``The 13th Warrior,'' $8.4 million.  
</P>
<P>
	4. ``Bowfinger,'' $7 million.  
</P>
<P>
	5. ``The Thomas Crown Affair,'' $6.1 million.  
</P>
<P>
	6. ``Chill Factor,'' $5.7 million.  
</P>
<P>
	7. ``Mickey Blue Eyes,'' $5.2 million.  
</P>
<P>
	8. ``The Blair Witch Project, $3.8 million.  
</P>
<P>
	9. ``The Muse,'' $3.5 million.  
</P>
<P>
	10. ``The Astronaut's Wife,'' $3.4 million.  
</P>
</TEXT>
